<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Receives Warm Welcome in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- On his first tour to France as
premier of China, Zhu Rongji has been cordially received by his
hosts since his arrival on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
To honor the Chinese leader, French President Jacques Chirac
hosted a luncheon at the Elysee Presidential Palace on Monday.
</P>
<P>
When the moment came for the host and guest to say good-bye in
the palace courtyard, Chirac expressed his respect for the Chinese
leader by clasping his hands together in a traditional Chinese
gesture.
</P>
<P>
His eyes filled with emotion, Zhu waved his hand to the
president and to journalists covering the moving scene.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with some 400 delegates from the French
employers' association, Conseil National du Patronat Francaise, at
a brunch earlier in the morning, Zhu received lengthy applause
from the French entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question by a representative from the Alcatel
telecommunications group, Zhu recalled an incident as the mayor of
Shanghai when he joined in an effort to establish one of the first
joint-venture telecommunications company in China -- the Shanghai
Bell Company.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said jokingly that it was no time for him to negotiate for
new contracts with French companies, but that they could do it
later "under the table."
</P>
<P>
"If I did that, the British might accuse me of lacking
`transparency'," said Zhu to the amusement of his audience.
</P>
<P>
On his visit to the Rodin Museum on Sunday, Zhu praised his
guide, Jacqueline Samson, for her explanation of works by the
French artist August Rodin.
</P>
<P>
Ms. Samson was close to tears when Premier Zhu shook her hands
and gave her a gift. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
