<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1200 GMT, April 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Commission decided Monday to take
legal action against some European Union (EU) member states for
failing to prevent water pollution.
</P>
<P>
The commission, an executive body of the EU, is sending
warnings to Britain, Portugal, Finland and France, while preparing
to take Spain to the European Court of Justice for disregarding
the commission's regulation concerning pollution by nitrates.
</P>
<P>
The commission requires EU member states to carry out
monitoring of surface water and groundwater to identify and
designate vulnerable zones for pollution caused by agricultural
sources. (BC-EU-Water Pollution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia will axe about 120,000 air servicemen,
including 40 generals, as part of a move to transform its air
defense force, a Russian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 officers will be transferred to other military
districts, and over 300 military establishments will be closed,
the Krasnaya Zvezda quoted a Russian officer as saying.
(Russia-Air Servicemen-Dismissal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji Monday called on French
enterprises to be more engaged in China, as the country is the
best for investment in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"I think China is the best place for investment in Asia. But
it is up to you to decide. Don't lose this opportunity," said
Zhu when addressing more than 200 heads of French enterprises
at a breakfast organized by France's national employers'
association CNPF.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that France played a very positive role at the ASEM
meeting held in London last week, because President Jacques Chirac
expressed deep sympathy and support to the Asian countries now
undergoing a financial crisis. (France-China-Zhu Rongji)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Forest fires have hit eight provinces in the
Philippines from January to April of 1998, a top official of the
National Disaster Coordinating Council said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The affected provinces include Benguet, Oriental Mindoro,
Palawan, Negros Occidental, Zamboanga del Norte, Davao del Norte,
Davao Oriental and Davao del Sur.
</P>
<P>
Fortunato Dejoras, executive officer of the council and office
of civil defense administrator, said a total of 14 towns and 46
villages in the eight provinces were affected by the conflagration
 which is said to have started by farmers practicing the
traditional "Kaingin" (slash and burn) method.
</P>
<P>
He said a total of 22,594 hectares of forest lands were also
destroyed by these fires. (Philippines-Forest Fires) 
</P>
</TEXT>
