<HEADLINE> Britain, France Ratify Nuclear Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain and France
announced Monday that they have ratified the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by their permanent missions to the
United Nations in separate press releases.
</P>
<P>
The British mission said Monday that British Ambassador John
Weston deposited the UK instruments of ratification at the U.N.
Headquarters in New York and French Ambassador Alain Dejammet
deposited the French instruments at the same ceremony.
</P>
<P>
France ratified the CTBT "jointly with the United Kingdom," the
French mission said.
</P>
<P>
This joint action "illustrates the solidarity of their approach
to issues of nuclear non-proliferation and nuclear disarmament,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
Since the CTBT was opened for signing in New York on September
24, 1996, 149 countries have signed and 12 have ratified including
Britain and France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
