<HEADLINE> 6 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Six rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in recent military operations by
Turkish government troops, the Anatolia News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a statement issued by the Office of the Emergency
Rule Region as saying that their bodies were recovered near Dicle,
a county in the southeastern province of Diyarbakir.
</P>
<P>
In addition, four PKK members were captured and seven others
surrendered to the government troops in the provinces of
Diyarbakir and Tunceli.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 14-year-old war against the
Turkish government for the establishment of an independent Kurdish
state in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Around 30,000 rebels, civilians and soldiers have died in
clashes between the government troops and the PKK, according to
official figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
