<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Urges Africa to Pursue Health for All </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Regional Director for Africa of
the World Health Organisation (WHO) Ebrahim Samba urged African
states to pursue health for all here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at the opening of a three-day African Federation
for Technology in Health Care conference, Samba said "Health for
all by the year 2000" slogan should motivate African countries to
pursue the goal of providing health for all.
</P>
<P>
He said that there was need to set target dates to enable
governments' work towards their objectives with vigor.
</P>
<P>
WHO believed health for all in Africa could be achieved, said
Samba, not by governments alone, but through equal partnerships
with the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Samba said there was a general complaint of inappropriate
technology among most African states and health practitioners,
which needed to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, appropriate technology did not mean that the
continent wanted cheap technology to ensure health for all.
</P>
<P>
He said that lack of appropriate technology was also forcing
most people to go overseas in search for medical help.
</P>
<P>
The conference, being attended by more than 100 health experts
from 20 African and six European countries, seeks to implement
WHO 1994/95 resolutions on health on the continent and to find
new ways to improve health provision services through improved
technology.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Health and Child Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps
said there is need for African countries to develop a health
procurement system that does not leave the continent open to
exploitation by foreign industries.
</P>
<P>
He said that a well managed system would ensure that Africa
procured not only durable but good, safe and appropriate
equipment for use in health institutions.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the limited number of hospital engineers
and inadequate preventive maintenance and maintenance skills
among the users of medical equipment also remained an area of
major concern on the continent.
</P>
<P>
He called for the harmonization of health ministries and the
medical technology industry to improve and ensure relevant
equipments necessary for the provision of basic and advanced
health care.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a health care equipment exhibition was organized by
FSG Wedimedia Ltd of the United Kingdom and USK International
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
