<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Condemns Riga Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia Monday sharply denounced a
blast near the Russian Embassy in Riga, Latvia's capital,
describing the incident as "outrageous."
</P>
<P>
The bomb went off 35 meters from the Russian Embassy at 2300
GMT Sunday. Four cars were damaged, but there were no casualties,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The blast provided new grounds for even greater concern over
anti-Russian terrorist activities and rising nationalism and
extremism in the Baltic nation, said the Russian Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"Explosions rock Latvia, monuments are vandalized, fascists are
raising their heads," the ministry said, adding that Russia is
"demanding that Latvian authorities take drastic measures to
punish the guilty."
</P>
<P>
Latvian Interior Minister Ziedonis Cevers said on television
that the bomb was a landmine, and that police were taking
additional security measures in the wake of this blast and another
that caused extensive damage to the Latvian capital's only
synagogue last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The explosions came against a backdrop of deteriorating
relations between Riga and Moscow, which are at odds over Latvia's
treatment of ethnic Russians living in the Baltic country.
</P>
<P>
In early March Latvian police forcefully disbanded a
Russian-speaking pensioners rally in Riga, which increased tension
in Russian-Latvian relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
