<HEADLINE> Pak to Play Fundamental Role in Emerging World Order: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said
here Monday that Pakistan is poised to "play a fundamental role in
the emerging world order."
</P>
<P>
Addressing civil and military officers at the National Defense
College, Sharif said that the world is developing towards
multipolarization with close and productive cooperation between
nations.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who deliberated on various crucial national and
international issues concerning Pakistan, said that he has again
held out the olive branch of meaningful dialogue to the newly
elected prime minister of India.
</P>
<P>
"We await a clear pledge of sincerity towards the peaceful
resolution of the Jammu and Kashmir issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed the need to give thought to the
structural reforms of international institutions to enable them to
meet the challenges of a rapidly changing world.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's relations with the Muslim world will continue to be
in the forefront of all Islamic causes, said Sharif. "Our goal
will remain not only to interact closely with all Muslim countries
but also to strengthen the unity and solidarity of the Islamic
community," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the Afghan issue, Sharif said that so long as Afghanistan
continued to be ravaged by war, the enormous potential for
interaction with the resource-rich Central Asian republics will
never be realized, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed the confidence that efforts by his government
to bring the warring factions in Afghanistan to the negotiating
table will succeed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
