<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ruling Party Chairman Exonerates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe African National Union
(Patriotic Front) Chairman Joseph Msika said Monday Parliament
Speaker Cyril Ndebele will not be tried by the party.
</P>
<P>
Msika told the Zimbabwe News Agency that Ndebele will not be
tried for advising that Masvingo Central MP Dzikamai Mavhaire
should be given parliamentary immunity for utterances made in the
house. Msika said that as Chairman of the Disciplinary Committee
he had the final say on whether or not Ndebele had a case to
answer.
</P>
<P>
The speaker was strongly rebuked by President Robert Mugabe
for advising that Mavhaire should not be answerable for his
"Mugabe must go" statements.
</P>
<P>
"The speaker has no case to answer. He may have made an
omission in his advice but that does not warrant him to be
tried," Msika said.
</P>
<P>
He said the contradiction coming from ZANU (PF) Secretary for
Administration Didymus Mutasa who is insisting that Ndebele must
be disciplined was immaterial.
</P>
<P>
"Mutasa is not the chairman of the party and he cannot say
anything final," said Musika.
</P>
<P>
He said that the party central committee meeting, which
suspended Mavhaire from holding any party position for two years,
had not decided on what to do with the speaker.
</P>
<P>
Regarding his utterances in the parliament, Nebele said that
he has no apologies to make for his advice as he was following
the correct provisions of the law.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Information, Posts and Telecommunications
Minister Chen Chimutengwende welcomed President Robert Mugabe's
declaration that he will step down if the party congress said so.
</P>
<P>
The minister said in a statement that Mugabe's remarks should
clarify the matter once and for all and shut up those calling for
him, who has been at the helm for the past 18 years, to step
down.
</P>
<P>
"It is ZANU (PF) congress which elected him to power and it
is, therefore, proper and democratic that the same congress
should be the only body that can change the position," he said.
</P>
<P>
Other individuals, political analysts, economists, leaders of
the labour movement and human rights activists have also called
on Mugabe (74 ) to resign, citing economic hardships which have
escalated since the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister attacked them, saying that they were
misguided to think that Zimbabwe had an economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
