<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Defense Force Chief Resigns Over False </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Monday accepted resignation by National Defense
Force (SANDF) Chief General Georg Meiring after a military
intelligence report he handed to Mandela was found fraudulant.
</P>
<P>
"President Mandela with regret decided to accede to the
request of Chief of the SANDF Georg Meiring to allow him to
retire early," Cabinet Secretary Jakes Gerwel was quoted by South
African Press Association (SAPA) as saying in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Gerwel said Mandela has described Meiring's decision as
appropriate and honorable.
</P>
<P>
He said Mandela would confer with his cabinet on Meiring's
successor.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Meiring announced his decision to resign,
saying it was related to a military intelligence report about a
plot to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
"I have, after due consideration of all the facts, decided
that it would be in the best interests of the SANDF if I would
ask the president to suspend my contract and allow me to retire
on early pension without prejudice," SAPA quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Meiring said his decision to retire was not
acknowledgement that he had acted wrongly or with sinister
motives.
</P>
<P>
He said he was the individual responsible for addressing the
mistrust unleashed by the inaccurate report, which he handed
personally to Mandela on February 5.
</P>
<P>
The report, which claimed that a handful of senior African
National Congress (ANC) members were plotting a coup, has
triggered widespread controversy in the country since media
published parts of its content in late March.
</P>
<P>
It alleged that among others, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela,
Mandela's ex-wife, SANDF Chief of Staff Siphiwe Nyanda and former
ANC member and now opposition United Democratic Movement
co-leader Bantu Holomisa were involved in the plot.
</P>
<P>
"My position of trust has been unsettled by the report, which
leaves me no choice but to come to this decision... My early
retirement therefore is an effort to restore the trust in... the
SANDF," Meiring said.
</P>
<P>
Should Mandela approve his request, his last day of service
would be May 31, Meiring said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a judicial commission appointed by Mandela found
that the handling of the report had been flawed and the report
had no substance. The government accused certain elements in the
military of trying to destabilize the country by launching a
disinformation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
