<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Ruling Party Wins Appeal on Colors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Lesotho Congress
for Democracy (LCD) could continue to use its party colors, the
Lesotho Court of Appeal ruled Monday, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The appeal court overode a High Court ruling on February 25
that the LCD should not use the black, green and red colors,
which the opposition Basutoland Congress Party (BCP) argued were
similar to theirs.
</P>
<P>
On submission by the BCP that similarities in colors would
confuse supporters of the two parties, the LCD argued that at
elections, political parties did not display colors on flags but
only their party symbols, which must be registered only in black
and white in accordance with electoral laws.
</P>
<P>
The colors and flags of parties therefore played no importance
in influencing or directing people as to how to vote.
</P>
<P>
BCP deputy leader, Tshiliso Makhakhe said he upheld the
independence of the judiciary and accepted and respected the
decision of the appeal court. However, he said he was totally
"surprised" at the appeal court's order since the contested
colors are a mark of the BCP.
</P>
<P>
The LCD, led by Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle, broke away from
the then ruling BCP in June last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone: Trial of Junta Coupists Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The trial of the first batch of 21
suspected coupists of Sierra Leone's ousted military junta
continued Monday, with charges varying from treason, murder and
arson.
</P>
<P>
Those charged with treason and arson will face death penalty,
according to a British Broadcasting Corporation report monitored
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The trial began a week ago and those appeared before the court
included five civilians who acted as ministers and deputy
ministers under the former military regime.
</P>
<P>
Others included former junta spokesman, arms dealer, popular
broadcaster, and the former secretary of president Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
According to the attorney-general, many more will be charged
as the police investigations are completed and the results of the
investigations are made known.
</P>
<P>
There are close to 200 persons, both military and civilian,
who are under investigations and those who are not involved will
be released immediately, he said.
</P>
<P>
The military junta, which toppled the legitimate government of
Kabbah in a coup last May, was dislodged by the west African
peacekeeping force in mid-February, with the president restored
on March 10.
</P>
<P>
The government has vowed to penalize members and collaborators
of the junta regime for the nationwide destruction and chaos
caused by the coupists and those cooperated with them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
