<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garang Reaffirms Separation of Religion, State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- A Sudanese rebel leader has
reaffirmed his stand that religion should be separated from
state, asking the Khartoum government to accept this as a basic
reality and principle, the Kenya News Agency (KNA) reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
John Garang, Chairman of the Sudan People's Liberation
Movement (SPLM), was quoted as saying last weekend at Kenya-Sudan
border that religion was a matter of personal belief.
</P>
<P>
On self-determination for the people of southern Sudan, he
said that this was a fundamental human right which the people of
Sudan were entitled to.
</P>
<P>
Garang, also Chairman of the Sudan People's Liberation Army
(SPLA), was speaking when he met a special delegation from the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD).
</P>
<P>
He commended President Daniel arap Moi's efforts in trying to
bring to an end the conflict in southern Sudan and President Moi
is the chairman of the IGAD Peace Initiative on Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The delegation which consists of representatives from Kenya,
Uganda, Ethiopia and Eritrea had visited Kenya, Sudan, Uganda,
Ethiopia and Eritrea before meeting with Garang.
</P>
<P>
The KNA report said that while meeting the SPLA/SPLM chairman,
IGAD peace delegation presented the Sudanese government with
proposals on ceasefire and the new constitution.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting between the rebel movement and the Khartoum
government is expected to be held in Kenya's capital of Nairobi
later this month.
</P>
<P>
The previous peace talks failed to reach agreements due to the
contentious issue of separation of religion and state, and the
question of self-determination for the people of southern Sudan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
