<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-East Bloc States Said to Be Still Spying on West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Despite efforts to join the Western
military alliance NATO, former East Bloc countries, like Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic, are still spying on their would-be
allies, intelligence sources in Bonn confirmed Monday a report in
the news weekly Der Spiegal.
</P>
<P>
The news magazine reported that former East Bloc countries have
been trying to place agents at high levels in the NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic are among the first wave
of Eastern European countries to be admitted into NATO. But in the
personnel proposed for their future NATO embassies, they had tried
to include many known spies, who however had been rejected by
NATO.
</P>
<P>
There are still close ties between intelligence agents from the
countries seeking NATO membership and Russian espionage
organizations, said Der Spiegal citing NATO security organs.
</P>
<P>
It added that officials in Brussels feared that Poland would
pass NATO secrets to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The magazine also quoted Peter Frisch, chief of Germany's
domestic intelligence service, as saying that of the three
countries, Poland in particular has not reduced its espionage
activities in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Poland has denied the charges and said it has already dismissed
600 of the 1,000 foreign intelligence agents during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the Spiegal report, the intelligence sources in Bonn
also said that there are at least hundreds of spies from the
ex-East Bloc countries working currently in Germany, with those
from Russia and Romania being the most active.
</P>
<P>
They said Russian agents focused their efforts on NATO and
defense information, and telecommunications and computer
technology as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
