<HEADLINE> U.S. Energy Secretary to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Energy Secretary Federico
Pena Monday announced his resignation, citing "personal and
family" reasons.
</P>
<P>
Pena, who served as transportation secretary in Clinton's first
term, submitted his letter of resignation to President Bill
Clinton Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, Pena said he had decided to resign
because he wanted to spend more time with his family and to focus
more on his children.
</P>
<P>
"There is never a perfect time for a decision like this, but I
believe that after five-and-a-half years as a member of the
Clinton Cabinet, the time is now right" to depart, said Pena in a
memo sent to department employees.
</P>
<P>
Pena, 51, had planned to leave Washington at the end of
Clinton's first term. He reminded reporters Monday that he already
had put his Washington house up for sale when he was asked by the
president to head the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
Pena said he planned to depart on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Early in 1997, Pena, the former Denver mayor agreed to take
over the Energy Department, but has made it clear he likely would
not want to remain the full four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
