<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Power Generation Increases in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Nuclear electricity generation
rose by 9.6 percent in 1997 to provide over 60 percent of
Belgium's electricity, Foratom reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Generation records were also set in Finland, France, Germany,
Spain, Switzerland and Britain in the past year, according to
Foratom, or the European Atomic Forum that is the trade
association of the European nuclear industry.
</P>
<P>
Foratom Secretary General Wolf Schmidt Kuster described the
past year as having witnessed nuclear energy continue to be the
largest single source of carbon-free electricity in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear electricity now accounts for over 30 percent of the
total generation in Europe and is believed to provide a
competitive and environmentally beneficial source of electricity
as the electricity market is deregulating in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Despite the drag triggered by the Asian economic slowdown, fuel
cycle companies in Europe still won large multi-year contracts
from foreign governments last year for clean-up work at former
military sites.
</P>
<P>
European technologies for nuclear waste management is set to be
a major growth sector for employment and profits in the future,
according to the Foratom report.
</P>
<P>
Foratom hailed nuclear electricity generation as an alternative
to help reduce greenhouse gas emissions in that unlike thermal
power plants, nuclear power plants do not emit carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power plants are claimed to help offset greenhouse gas
emissions by 700 million tons each year, Foratom said.
</P>
<P>
But the Foratom report did not mention the danger a
Chernobyl-type nuclear power plant incident can cause to the
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
