<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls for Cease-Fire in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Monday urged all Afghan parties to stop the fighting and to agree
immediately on a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The council also called on the parties to engage in a political
dialogue for national reconciliation, a lasting political
settlement of the conflict and the formation of a broad-based
fully representative government.
</P>
<P>
The council said in a presidential statement adopted Monday
that it reiterates its call to all countries to stop interference
immediately.
</P>
<P>
It points to the fact that "the foreign interference continues
unabated in the form of the supply of war-making materials to the
factions, reinforcing the reluctance of faction leaders to engage
in serious political dialogue with one another."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council said the United Nations, as a universally
recognized intermediary, must continue to play its central and
impartial role in international efforts towards a peaceful
resolution of the Afghanistan conflict.
</P>
<P>
It is concerned with the sharp deterioration of the
humanitarian situation in several areas in Central and Northern
Afghanistan, while strongly urging the Taliban to let the
humanitarian agencies attend to the needs of the population.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan factions have actively engaged in arms replenishment
throughout the last months.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council supports the steps of U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to launch investigations into alleged
mass killings of prisoners of war and civilians in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
