<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Clinton Hold Telephone Conversation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday held a telephone conversation
focused on bilateral relations and the upcoming G-8 meeting, the
Interfax news agency cited Yeltsin's press service as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Eight industrialized countries is to hold its
meeting in Birmingham, a U.S. city, in May this year, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
During the half-an-hour phone talk, the two leaders also
considered the two nations' relations with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Clinton praised a recent meeting between Yeltsin, French
President Jacques Chirac and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, saying
the three-nation summit, held near Moscow, had been a good signal
for the international community.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Clinton about the recent visit by Namibian
President Sam Nujoma and called for deeper involvement of African
countries in international politics.
</P>
<P>
The two men also expressed satisfaction with interaction
between the Russian Foreign Ministry and the U.S. State
Department, primarily in settling crises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
