<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Repatriates 353 Illegal Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Angola repatriated 353 illegal
immigrants in northern Uige Province in the first quarter of the
year, the official in charge of immigration and border affairs
told media Monday.
</P>
<P>
Almeida Ribeiro, head of the immigration and border affairs
authorities, told reporters that of the 353 repatriates, 346 are
from Congo, three from Gambia, three from Mali and one from Sao
Tome and Principe. They all entered through the border in Uige
Province and engaged in illegal trade and other unlawful
activities.
</P>
<P>
These illegal immigrants returned home on vehicles arranged by
the Angolan interior ministry.
</P>
<P>
As was disclosed by Ribeiro, the immigration and border
affairs authorities began sorting out illegal immigrants late
1997.
</P>
<P>
Except those having been repatriated, there are still 150
illegal immigrants to be sent home. Many of them are now working
in non-governmental organizations and other economic sectors,
Ribeiro said, adding that others are engaged in illegal
activities while evading checks.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of 1992 when civil war broke out again in
Angola, many illegal immigrants swarmed into the country.
</P>
<P>
Some of these immigrants engaged themselves in illegal
exploitation of diamond in Angola's northeastern provinces of
Lunda-Norte and Lunda-Sul, and some engaged in illegal trade in
northern provinces of Uige and Mlanje, and the capital city of
Luanda, greatly destabilizing the economic and social orders in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have been doing the repatriation work since
Angola's two warring sides signed the Lusaka Peace Accord and
ceased fire in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In August 1996, the Angolan police launched the Cancer-2
operation, sorting out many illegal immigrants, especially those
engaged in unlawful trade.
</P>
<P>
So far, 5,000 illegal immigrants have been repatriated, most
of whom are Africans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
