<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Arabs Protest House Demolition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Arabs on Monday
observed a general strike and marched to protest against what
they called persistent discrimination and demolition of their
homes by Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
Although police were keeping vigil against possible
disturbances, the protests passed without major incidents of
violence.
</P>
<P>
The strike and demonstrations were called to protest the
police during last weekend's violent clashes between Arab
residents and police in a Bedouin village near the northern town
of Shfaram.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of protesters and police were wounded duing the
clashes, which were triggered by police's attempt to demolish
three homes allegedly rebuilt without official licenses.
</P>
<P>
In Arab towns in northern Israel, schools, shops and offices
were closed as part of the general strike. Holding Palestinian
flags and green Islamic Movement flags, about 10,000 Arab
protesters marched from Shfaram to the Bedouin village Sahali,
where last weekend's clashes erupted.
</P>
<P>
Following the march, dozens of Arabs began rebuilding the
three demolished homes that ignited the recent violence. The
police did not intervene apparently for fear of escalating the
tensions.
</P>
<P>
The recent violence between Israeli Arabs and police signaled
the increasing tensions between the government and the country's
one million Arab population, who closely associate with
Palestinians in the territories. Arab citizens have been
protesting years of discrimination and confiscation of properties
by Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
In order to calm the anger of the Arab population Monday,
Israeli leaders vowed to pay more attention to their
well-being. Tourism Minister Moshe Katsav, who is in charge of
Arab affairs, admitted that a mistake was made Saturday because
the police did not consult with local Arab leaders before
demolishing the buildings.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman has expressed concern about the rising
tensions between Arabs and the government and voiced sympathy
toward the Arabs, saying that many of them are living under
critical conditions. He said that he would tour the northern
region on Thursday to hear complaints from local Arabs.
</P>
</TEXT>
