<HEADLINE> Mitchell Fine-Tunes Draft Peace Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
London, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland peace talk
chairman George Mitchell is holding last-minute talks Monday over
his draft proposals for constitutional change.
</P>
<P>
Differences between the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) and the
Social Democratic and Labor Party (SDLP) over a new assembly have
delayed publication of the blueprint, according to a BBC TV
report.
</P>
<P>
The rival parties also held a succession of talks sessions
Monday to try and bridge their differences and speed a long-sought
peace settlement for Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The pro-British UUP and the pro-Irish SDLP were having a second
meeting to nail down an agreement on how key aspects of a new
Northern Ireland parliament should operate.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Britain and Ireland will put any overall
deal to referendums on both sides of the border, probably on May
22.
</P>
<P>
A peace accord could see elections around June 25 to a
parliament of between 90 and 110 seats.
</P>
<P>
According to political sources, Britain and Ireland submitted a
joint paper earlier on aspects of a contentious proposed
all-Ireland ministerial council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
