<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-06 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hamas Rejects PNA Findings on Sharif's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian radical group
Hamas rejected on Monday the findings of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) over the killing of its activist Muhi Sharif.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Hamas, or Islamic Resistance Movement,
condemned PNA's investigation results as "lies."
</P>
<P>
PNA security officials said Monday that Sharif was killed by
rivals in an internal struggle for leadership of Hamas, clearing
Israel of its responsibility in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Hamas' statement attributed PNA's announcement of its findings
to the pressure of Israel and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Hamas finds a strong and direct link between the issuing of
these weak rumors and American and Zionist pressures on the
(Palestinian National) Authority to exonerate the criminal and
transforming the victim into the criminal," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has vowed to avenge Sharif's death by attacking Jewish
targets both inside and outside Israel.
</P>
<P>
"In Hamas, we affirm to our people, that the blood of martyr
Sharif did not spill in vain and these rumors will not prevent
Hamas from making its decision and choosing the path of struggle,"
the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was Hamas' chief bomb maker and most wanted by Israel
for masterminding several suicide bombing attacks which killed
dozens of Israelis. His body was found on March 29 in the West
Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials initially accused Israel of shooting
Sharif to death before dumping his body in an explosive-rigged car
and detonated it.
</P>
<P>
Israel has categorically denied the accusation and warned that
if Hamas launches terror attacks on Israel, it will hold the PNA
responsible for it. The U.S. also called on the PNA to prevent
Hamas from taking such actions.
</P>
<P>
Hamas' statement said that it is also investigating the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Israel was behind the killing and the PNA also "carries part of
the responsibilities of this crime that happened on the land under
its control," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
