<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia: Maternal,Infant Mortality High: Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of Health
Adem Ibrahim said Monday that Ethiopia is among those developing
countries with high maternal and infant mortality rate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference to mark the World Health Day
which falls on Tuesday, April 7 under the theme of "Pregnancy is
special -- let us make it safe", Minister Adem noted that
Ethiopia is facing high maternal and infant mortality rate due to
lack of health services and malnutrition, infection during
delivery as well as poor sanitation.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that millions of Ethiopian women underwent
the risk of pregnancy without knowing that they could avoid it if
they wanted to.
</P>
<P>
This trend should not be allowed to continue since the
interventions that make motherhood safe are known and the
resources needed are available, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Making motherhood safe is one of the prime concerns of the
ministry of health," the minister said, adding that the Ethiopian
government has displayed its commitment to the improvement of
women's living standard by drawing various policies that ensure
the well-being of women and children.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the World Health
Organization (WHO) here Monday, in such developing countries as
Ethiopia, the maternal mortality rate is on average about 870 per
100,000 live births. 
</P>
</TEXT>
