<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Discuss Stronger Ties With Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
spoke with Russian President Boris Yeltsin Monday about his recent
trip to Africa, and suggested they discuss the continent at a
meeting next month in England.
</P>
<P>
In a 30-minute telephone conversation, Clinton reviewed his
12-day visit to six African nations, and noted that the continent
"was sometimes the venue for superpower rivalry" during the Cold
War, said White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
"He suggested that they could perhaps talk about ways in which
Russia and the United States could cooperate together on
initiatives related to Africa," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin will meet in May at the summit of seven
industrialized nations plus Russia in Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said that Yeltsin offered an assessment of the
prospects of confirmation for Prime Minister-Designate Sergei
Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
Clinton emphasized his desire for the Russian parliament to
ratify the START II arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also raised concerns about nuclear proliferation "and
stressed how importantly we take the commitments that we've
received from the Russian Federation related to missile technology
transfer issues," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
