<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safe Motherhood, This Year's Theme: U.N. Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Monday reminded the world of taking care about women' health
as there are 600,000 maternal deaths a year globally.
</P>
<P>
In his message for World Health Day which falls on April 7,
Annan said this year's theme to observe the day is "Safe
Motherhood -- the health and survival of women during pregnancy
and childbirth."
</P>
<P>
Along the large number of deaths, private statistics put
pregnancy and childbirth related injuries to women at 50 million a
year in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. Population Fund (UNFPA), nearly three
fourths of the deaths are directly related to severe blooding,
infection, unsafe abortions, eclampsia and obstructed labor, while
maternal and newborn health services would cost only an average of
three U.S. dollars per person per year to prevent such deaths.
</P>
<P>
A consortium of U.N. and international agencies has launched a
year-long awareness campaign and called on governments and people
worldwide to commit to implementing measures to curb childbirth
related deaths and injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
