<HEADLINE> Cohen Says U.S. Troops to Remain in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said Monday that the United States expected to keep its 350
troops in Macedonia as part of a United Nations peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with Macedonian Defense Minister Lazar
Kitanoski, Cohen said he expected the mandate for the
international peacekeeping force to be extended past its
expiration date of August 31.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking to reporters at the photo session with Cohen,
Kitanoski said the American presence was vital to keeping at bay
the unrest that had shaken Bosnia, and now the Kosovo area of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"If not prevented, it could cause a domino effect around the
entire Balkans," Kitanoski said.
</P>
<P>
In Macedonia, the United Nations now has about 700 troops, half
from the United States and the rest from Scandinavian nations. The
peacekeepers were posted in the region in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
