<HEADLINE> Clinton to Hear on Mideast Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton will be
told on Monday evening the difficult situation in the Middle East
for a breakthrough of the peace process by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross, the White
House said.
</P>
<P>
"Ross will review where we are in the peace process," a White
House spokeswoman said. She did not make any elaboration on the
evening briefing.
</P>
<P>
Ross made a trip last week to the Middle East in an new effort
to break the year-long deadlock of the peace process by offering
new ideas on Israel's pullback on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But his proposals of Israel further ceding 13.1 percent of its
occupied West Bank have been rejected by the Israeli government on
the grounds of its security.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has admitted its envoy Ross could
not bridge the gap between Israel and the Palestinians over the
size of the Israeli pullback.
</P>
<P>
Albright last week said that the United States felt frustrated
over the continued impasse in the region and indicated the United
States might wash its hands as a broker as it could not go on
forever in such a stalemated situation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said last week they would decide in the
ensuing few days how to pursue peace efforts, following Ross's
latest trip, but indicated they expected Israeli and Palestinian
leaders to come up with better offers before then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
