<HEADLINE> Lawyers Waiting for Jones to Make Appeal Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The conservative foundation
supporting Paula Jones's sexual harassment lawsuit against U.S.
President Bill Clinton said Monday lawyers are still waiting to
hear if she wants to appeal a judge's decision dismissing the
suit.
</P>
<P>
A Rutherford Institute spokesman said that Jones still has to
get "focused" after last week's order, adding, "She's the one
who's going to make the final call," United Press International
reported.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, a federal judge in Arkansas ruled Jones had not
produced enough evidence to bring her suit against President
Clinton to a jury.
</P>
<P>
Jones claimed Clinton, as Arkansas governor, exposed himself
and made a crude sexual proposition in a Little Rock hotel suite
in 1991, and that her career as a low-level state employee
suffered after the rebuff.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. Judge Susan Webber Wright said even if Jones is
telling the truth -- a position the judge was required to take
before ending the case without trial -- Jones had not shown that
she was harmed by the alleged harassment.
</P>
<P>
Jones has 30 days from last week's ruling to file a notice of
appeal.
</P>
<P>
Almost immediately after last Wednesday's ruling, the
Rutherford Institute issued a statement saying Jones would appeal
to the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and to the Supreme Court
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Late Wednesday evening, however, the institute issued another
statement, saying, "an appeal is very likely but no final decision
has been made." 
</P>
</TEXT>
