<HEADLINE> UAE Calls for Enlarged Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
Monday called for an enlarged Arab summit to discuss Arab affairs,
UAE's official Wam news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone conversation with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan al-Nahyan
underlined the importance of holding "a gathering of Arab leaders
in the current period ... to bring the Arab nations out of the
disastrous situation."
</P>
<P>
He had hinted before that the Arab world is lack of strong
solidarity enabling them to speak in one voice when dealing with
Arab affairs.
</P>
<P>
The president said that there should be intensified efforts to
encourage those countries who are hesitating to attend such a
proposed summit to ensure it cover every Arab state.
</P>
<P>
"The gathering is in national interests of all (Arab
countries)," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has repeatedly urged all Arab states to attend an
emergency Arab summit to discuss Arab issues, in particular the
stalled Mideast peace process and the situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and some other Arab countries have reportedly expressed
their support to the UAE's appeal while others remain cautious
on commenting on it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
