<HEADLINE> US Welcomes Ratification of Nuclear Test Ban Treaty by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States welcomes the
ratification of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT)
by France and Britain, said the White House Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It represents a milestone in the global effort to reduce the
nuclear threat and to build a safer world," White House Spokesman
Mike McCurry said at a regular briefing when referring to the
ratification of the treaty by Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
"The president (Clinton) obviously expresses his gratitude to
President Chirac, Prime Minister Blair, in his statement, and
again calls on the United States Senate to give its advice and
consent to the CTBT this year," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The treaty is in the best interest of the United States because
its provisions will significantly further our nuclear
nonproliferation and arms control objectives and strengthen
international security, said McCurry.
</P>
<P>
Britain and France became the first nuclear powers to ratify a
treaty banning nuclear weapons tests on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the two countries turned over documents to
the United Nations' treaty section in New York signifying their
government's acceptance of the CTBT, which prohibits any kind of
nuclear weapons test explosion.
</P>
<P>
Britain's U.N. ambassador, John Weston, called the treaty "the
cornerstone of international efforts to prevent nuclear
proliferation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
