<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Calls for Hard Look at Afghan Question </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Monday that it is imperative for the U.N. and member
states to take a hard look at the external aspects of the Afghan
question and attempt to address them in earnest.
</P>
<P>
His remarks ware included in his report to the Security Council
which adopted a presidential statement today calling for stoppage
of foreign interference into the country's affairs.
</P>
<P>
Annan noticed that foreign military assistance continued to
pour into the country, inhibiting all peacemaking efforts by
felling the war machines of the mostly Uzbek, Tajik and Hazara
Northern Alliance and the predominantly Pushtoon Taliban.
</P>
<P>
"Despite their rhetorical support for the U.N. and a negotiated
settlement, neither side appeared ready to abandon the military
option," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the military situation there remained stalemated, with
occasionally flare-ups of fighting along the front lines between
Taliban and Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
"The continued fighting has not produced any significant
changes in the front lines but it has caused further destruction,
deaths, injuries and internal displacement of large numbers of
people," he said in the report.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian situation deteriorated sharply in Bamyan
Province where several hundred thousand people suffered from severe
food shortages, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
