<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda: 1994 Genocide Will Never Occur Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government
reiterated that the 1994 genocide in Rwanda will never occur
again.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here Monday by the Rwandan Embassy to
Ethiopia in commemoration of the fourth anniversary of the 1994
genocide in the country said, April 7 of 1994 is the symbol of
the igniter which triggered the abominable and barbaric crime --
genocide -- which cost more than one million Rwandan lives in
less than one hundred days.
</P>
<P>
It said, since 1994, the date of April 7 has become notorious
not only in the history of Rwanda, but also for the international
community as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The statement pointed out that "while paying tribute to the
memory of the victims of this heinous act, it would be important
for the international community to stand shoulder to shoulder and
commit itself not to tolerate or dismiss, let alone forget, this
tragedy that befell the people of Rwanda at the very beginning of
the month of April 1994."
</P>
<P>
It hoped that "the international community will renew its
solemn and unwavering commitment to ensure that this act of
barbarism which decimated the population of rwanda will never
occur again".
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation in Rwanda, the statement said,
"over the last four years, the government and people of Rwanda
have embarked on the task of national reconstruction: in that
regard, the political and administrative institutions have been
placed back on track, the ravaged economy is stirring again and
hopes is returning to the population".
</P>
<P>
"In commemorating the date of April 7, the international
community is duty-bound to remember and stand shoulder to
shoulder with the government and people of Rwanda in reiterating
the solemn and collective commitment that such an act never
occurs again," the statement concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
