<HEADLINE> Bahrain, U.S. Discuss Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and Bahrain's senior
military officials held talks Monday to discuss military
cooperation between Washington and Manama, Bahrain's official
Gulf News Agency (GNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Commander of Air Forces of the U.S. Central Command Carl
Franklin and Bahrain's Defense Minister and Vice Commander of the
Bahraini Defense Forces Sheikh Khalifa bin Ahmad al-Khalifa
discussed "the military cooperation and ways of boosting the
cooperation between the two sides," the GNA said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the talks between them focused on the extension of
deployment of U.S. military aircraft in Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Bahrain accepted Washington's request for the
extension of U.S. aircraft on its soil for a further 60 days
within the framework of a defense agreement signed between them
after the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain had previously consented, both last year and at the
beginning of this year, to a number of requests concerning the
deployment of U.S. military aircraft in its territory.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly deployed 36 warplanes, all belonging
to the U.S. Air Expeditionary Forces (AEF) in Bahrain, as part of
Washington's military buildup in the oil-rich Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. aircraft joined other U.S. forces in the Gulf region
to supervise the implementation of no-fly zone operation against
Iraq and sanctions imposed by the United Nations against Baghdad
in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zone in southern Iraq was imposed by U.S., British
and French forces in August 1991 to protect Shiite Muslim Iraqis
from reprisals after President Saddam Hussein's forces brutally
crushed their uprising soon after the end of 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
