<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Breaches Peace Accord: Archbishop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The archbishop of Liberia's
Catholic Church, Micheal Francis has accused the Liberian
government of failing to implement the agreement which calls for
the formation and training of the national army by the west
African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Senate on Monday afternoon, Bishop Francis said
that disarmament was finished to some extent and free and fair
elections were held.
</P>
<P>
However, the critical issue of restructuring the military and
security operators has been postponed and ignored, he said,
quoted by a British Broadcasting Corporation report monitored
here.
</P>
<P>
Under the Abuja peace accord, ECOMOG is mandated to be in
charge of the disarmament, provide security for the post-war
elections and participate in the re-building and training of the
Liberian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The archbishop recalled that initially all the former factions
had agreed to total disarmament and the formation of the new army
should be done regardless of factional loyalty.
</P>
<P>
But this has not happened, he observed. He also attributed
the current insecurity in the country to the failure to keep the
determination of the Abuja accord and the on-going attempt to
restructure the security forces by the government.
</P>
<P>
According to him, most of the problems Liberia is facing today
are rooted in the unfinished business of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
His statement caused unease in some members of the Senate. But
the archbishop said that "this is my honest and sincere opinion."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
