<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Favors Business-like Government, Not Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said he favored forming a government composed of business-like
people nominated by any faction, not a coalition government,
reports here said.
</P>
<P>
Opening a round-table meeting in the Kremlin on Tuesday,
Yeltsin proposed that formation of the government and nomination
of candidates should be "approached objectively, on business and
professional grounds, not on political considerations."
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin reportedly proposed forming a trilateral
committee among leaders of the government and both houses of
parliament at the "leading four" meeting on April 2.
</P>
<P>
At the April 2 meeting, which was attended by acting Prime
Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, lower house speaker Gennady Seleznyov
and Federal Council Chairman Yegor Stroyev, Yeltsin proposed that
the year 1998 be declared "a year without confrontation."
</P>
<P>
He also called for efforts to avoid conflicts and confrontation
within and between parliamentary factions, parties and
authoritative institutions.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's meeting, he urged participants to back
Kiriyenko's candidacy for premiership, so as not to delay his
appointment. Russia is now in a critical moment, the president
said, because the country has been without a government for two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The president said that he had suggested Kiriyenko "listen to
the deputies' proposals and refrain from making hasty moves."
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko told reporters after the round-table conference that
the meeting was constructive and that he was satisfied. He
believed that he would receive the support of the people.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Duma decided that it would vote on Kiriyenko's
nomination on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin dismissed his entire government two weeks ago and
nominated 35-year-old Kiriyenko, the former fuel and energy
minister, to the post of prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The president threatened on Monday to dissolve the parliament
if it vetoed the nominee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
