<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Japanese Graduates Join SDF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- More Japanese graduates of
universities and junior colleges are joining the Self-Defense
Forces (SDF) because of the stagnant economy and rising
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
One in four people who became middle-ranking members of the
Ground, Air and Maritime Self-Defense Forces in 1997 were
university or junior college graduates, Kyodo News reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1,200 who passed entrance exams for acceptance in the
SDF in 1997, 300 were university or college graduates, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The positions were previously dominated by high school
graduates. Officials blame the economy, which was once the world's
second largest but has since 1992 grown stagnant, on the change.
</P>
<P>
"In times of an economic slump, there is always an increase in
the number of people who want to become government employees
because of job security," an SDF official in charge of recruitment
said.
</P>
<P>
Those who want to be admitted to the SDF must pass an exam in
one of three categories: the top-level officer candidate exam for
posts filled mainly by university graduates; the middle-ranking
exam for senior high school graduates; or the general personnel
exam for posts filled by junior and senior high school graduates.
</P>
</TEXT>
