<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Chip Sales Rise in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- World semiconductor sales hit
10.52 billion U.S. dollars in February, the second highest
February total since 1990, the U.S. Semiconductor Industry
Association (SIA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Sales in the Americas, European and Asia-Pacific markets
climbed 3.3, 7.7 and 6.6 percent respectively from February 1997
figures.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the continued decline of the yen against the dollar
contributed to a sales fall of 13.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
While stronger than 1997 overall, world chip sales dipped 4
percent from January to February, the SIA said in its latest
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Sales in the Americas, European, Japanese and Asia-Pacific
markets decreased 4.1, 3.2, 4.8 and 4.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the SIA, sales in the first two months of this
year were consistent with the seasonal sales pattern seen in 1997
and were in line with the industry group's forecast.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, global sales surged in the second and third quarters
after a modest first quarter.
</P>
<P>
The SIA, formed in 1977, represents 90 percent of U.S.
semiconductor production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
