left Downing Street Tuesday afternoon on his way to Belfast to
save the peace after the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) rejected the
draft settlement plan.
</P>
<P>
Blair is to meet UUP leader David Trimble at Hillsborough
Castle later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The main pro-British party UUP rejected a document presented by
talks chairman George Mitchell earlier Tuesday. The feuding
parties in Northern Ireland are supposed to reach an agreement on
the basis of the draft plan before Thursday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
Mitchell's blueprint includes plans for a new parliament to run
the province's internal affairs alongside cross-border bodies that
Protestants fear will grow into an all-Irish state.
</P>
<P>
Blair's official spokesman said earlier in the day the prime
minister was ready to go to Belfast if he was needed there.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the Ulster Unionists' rejection of the peace plan
put forward by talks chairman George Mitchell, a spokesman for
Blair said the document was not intended to be final.
</P>
<P>
"No one has been asked to accept this document as it stands. It
exists as a basis for discussion and negotiation," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman in Dublin said Irish Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern would travel to Belfast Tuesday night or Wednesday
morning for talks with local leaders. 
