<HEADLINE> Crime Rate Falls in UK Amid Future Rise Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Crime in England and Wales fell by
almost 9 percent last year, the fifth consecutive annual drop,
according to government figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But property crime may rise in the long term as the economy
flourishes, as shown by research from the statistics department of
the Home Office, or the interior ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures, the number of offenses reported to
the police last year was down by about a fifth from 1992 levels,
the fifth consecutive annual fall.
</P>
<P>
Violent crime rose by 2 percent and sex crime was up by 7
percent in 1997. House burglary and car crime fell by 14 percent
across England and Wales.
</P>
<P>
"It is obviously pleasing to see that crime is heading in the
right direction, but we must not be complacent," junior minister
Alun Michael said.
</P>
<P>
"Economic factors may well create an upward pressure on
property crime in the future," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
