<HEADLINE> DuPont Locates 900-Million-Dollar Venture in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- US-based chemical giant DuPont
decided to locate a 900-million-US-dollar joint venture in south
China's Dongfang city, Hainan province.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from DuPont China, the company has made a
breakthrough in negotiations with the China National Offshore Oil
Company (CNOOC) on supply of natural gas for the joint venture
recently.
</P>
<P>
The site of the joint venture is located in the port city on
the island province.
</P>
<P>
DuPont and BASF Akliengesellschaft of Germany will have equal
investment in the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
"We remain totally committed to this joint venture, although it
has taken longer to reach this point than we anticipated," said
Eduard J. Van Wely, DuPont Senior vice president responsible for
the company's worldwide nylon business and the Asia Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Sources from DuPont said that the joint venture is well along
in going through procedures for government approval.
</P>
<P>
The nylon intermediates factory will use BASF technology to
turn China's natural gas into raw materials for producing nylon.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the factory is planned to break earth in early
1999. Upon completion, the factory will become a base for DuPont
to produce and sell nylon intermediates in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The factory is expected to turn out 150,000 tons of
caprolactam, the major material for production of nylon 6 polymer,
every year.
</P>
<P>
This joint venture will be the largest investment project that
DuPont has ever had in China. It will enable the company to meet
the target of investing one billion US dollars in the country by
2000.
</P>
<P>
Since entering China market in 1984, DuPont has already set up
11 wholly-owned or joint venture factories and four representative
offices in seven coastal cities in the country. Total investment
of DuPont in China has exceeded 300 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
