<HEADLINE> France, U.S. Strike Deal on Free Air Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- France and the United States struck
a deal Tuesday on establishing free air space between them,
allowing free competition between airline companies of the two
countries, said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Dominique Perreau, director for economic and financial affairs
in the French Foreign Ministry, and Joel Spiro, under-secretary
for transport of the U.S. State Department, signed a five-year
agreement in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, to be formalized within weeks by the foreign
ministers of the two countries before coming into force in June,
said that France and the United States will enlarge "in a
gradual and balanced way, the possibilities to be offered to air
transport companies."
</P>
<P>
Air France is eager to implement its agreements with U.S. air
companies on mutually representing each other in airports of each
other's country. They have been blocked from doing so by the
U.S. government because of the lack of an agreement with France on
free air space.
</P>
<P>
The United States has signed free air space agreements with a
number of other West European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
