<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabweans Encouraged to Invest in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambian senior officials said
Tuesday Zambia is ready to receive Zimbabwean commercial farmers
who are willing to invest in the country's agricultural sector,
according to Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an investment seminar here for Zimbabwean
commercial farmers who are in Zambia to explore investment
opportunities, Jazzman Chikwakwa, Deputy Minister of Commerce,
Trade and Industry, said the presence of Zimbabwean farmers will
even enhance trade between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Zambian government will continue
improving the investment climate in the country to enhance
economic development.
</P>
<P>
At the same occasion, Bwalya Ngandu, Zambia Investment Center
Director-General, assured the Zimbabwean farmers that they will
be given various incentives when they invest in his country
where less than 20 percent of the total 9 million hectares of
cultivatable land has been developed.
</P>
<P>
Ngandu stated that the capital equipment for farmers coming
into Zambia will not be taxed and that all income from
agriculture will be taxed at 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
He further explained that registered investors will be allowed
to own land in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Those who will come with an investment of 250,000 Dollars or
more will be given the status of self-employment that investors
in other sectors cannot enjoy, said Ngandu.
</P>
<P>
He also assured Zimbabwean farmers that they could have a
large market for their produce as Zambia is a member of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), which is
aiming to achieve a free trade area by 2000 and a customs union
with a zero tariff on products originating from within the
market. 
</P>
