<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Safe-Pregnancy Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Health plans
to launch a national project next month to lower the mortality
rate of pregnant women and infants by improving maternity
service.
</P>
<P>
The "Safe Motherhood" project aims to increase the proportion
of hospital births among pregnant women, according to Xiang
Xiaoying, an official with the ministry's Department of Woman and
Child Health.
</P>
<P>
Women who run a high risk in childbirth will be given more
care, and the rate of child birth defects is expected to drop
after implementing the project, said Xiang, who declined to give
more details.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to a 50 percent decline in the current death
rate of pregnant women by the year 2000," she said. "It is also a
goal which the Chinese government promised the international
community to achieve."
</P>
<P>
Today's World Health Day also focused on safe pregnancies and
childbirth, as well as health care for mothers. Chinese medical
personnel provided street-side health counseling at some downtown
areas of Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
China reported that 62 of every 100,000 pregnant women died
prior to or during childbirth in 1996, far below the world average
of 430 persons per 100,000 people, and the level in developing
countries of 480 persons per 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
However, the mortality rate for pregnant women in China's poor
rural areas was around 200 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
"The deadly causes included hemorrhaging, hypertension,
amniotic embolism, heart attacks, and inaccessible maternity
services," Xiang said.
</P>
<P>
"A national survey found that the rate of in-hospital
childbirth was lower than 20 percent in some areas. Almost half of
those who died in pregnancy died at their homes or on the road to
a hospital," she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
