<HEADLINE> Celebrations Planned to Mark HK's Return Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) is actively considering
various celebration events to mark the first anniversary of Hong
Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
David Lan, secretary for Home Affairs, said this in a replay to
a question on whether the government has any plan to celebrate the
event, at a two-day plenary session of the Provisional Legislative
Council that was opened here Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting Lan said that 1997/98 will be a most
significant and memorable year.
</P>
<P>
Following the smooth transition, he said the newly established
HKSAR has continued to function in a steady and progressive
manner, with the concept of "one country, two systems" and
principles of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high
degree of autonomy fully realized.
</P>
<P>
Lan said July 1 this year will be a time to look back on the
achievement of the HKSAR during its first year in existence.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from having it declared as a public holiday, the
Administration is actively considering various celebration events
to mark the occasion," he said.
</P>
<P>
As regards details and expenditure of such activities, he said:
"I can assure members that we will, as usual, be prudent in
spending public funds."
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on whether there is any plan to launch
publicity campaigns abroad in this respect, Lan said: "the
Secretary for Trade and Industry has been coordinating plans for
our overseas Economic and Trade Offices to organize functions in
celebration of the HKSAR's first anniversary."
</P>
<P>
He said that activities range from cocktail reception, sit-down
dinner with cultural performances to organizing major business
conferences to show how the HKSAR could be a launching pad to
business opportunities in the Asia Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
"July 1 1998 will be an occasion for our overseas offices to
brief their host countries on our free and open economy as well as
our autonomy under the 'one country, two systems' principle," he
added. 
</P>
