<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Debate on Undeclared Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission called on
Tuesday for a debate on undeclared work as part of its effort to
redress the employment issue.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials estimated that undeclared work accounts
for between 7 and 16 percent of the European Union's gross
domestic product, or represents between 10 million and 28 million
jobs that correspond to between 7 and 19 percent of total declared
employment in the union.
</P>
<P>
Undeclared work is defined by the commission as paid activity
that is lawful in nature but not notified to the public
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive agency of the 15-nation union,
identified undeclared work as an issue of common concern for EU
member states in the employment field.
</P>
<P>
It called for member states to debate on how to tackle the
issue more effectively.
</P>
<P>
Undeclared work usually is found in labor-intensive, low-profit
sectors such as agriculture, construction, retail trade, catering,
domestic services or manufacturing and business services where
costs are the major factor of competition.
</P>
<P>
Undeclared work is found to employ four main groups of people:
second and multiple job holders, economically inactive population
such as students and early retirees, the unemployed and
third-country nationals illegally residing in the EU.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials claimed that undeclared work risks
undermining the financing and delivery of social protection and
public services.
</P>
<P>
The curtailment of receipts, officials explained, means a
reduction in the level of services the state can offer and this
creates a vicious circle as the government raises taxes to
continue to provide the services, thus creating more incentives to
undeclared work.
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn, European Commissioner responsible for employment
and social affairs, said Tuesday: "The European Employment
Strategy, in particular the Employment Guidelines, now provides an
opportunity for combating undeclared work through EU coordinated
action if this is deemed necessary."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner expected a wide-ranging discussion that would
result in an action at EU level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Official Expects Polio to Be Eradicated Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) will make concerted efforts with its member countries for
the global eradication of diseases in the near future such as
polio, a WHO official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Infectious diseases are no longer a major issue for WHO; we
hope that polio and some other infectious diseases can be
eradicated in the near future," said Dr. Roderick W.K. Gee, WHO's
chief representative in China, at a meeting to mark the 50th
anniversary of WHO's establishment.
</P>
<P>
Gee said the Western Pacific region countries, including China,
are on the edge of eradicating polio and leprosy.
</P>
<P>
However, many new health problems brought by the rapid growth
of an aging population, the emergence of new diseases and
re-emergence of some old ones are posing a new challenge to
humans, he said, calling for further worldwide cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and new Health Minister Zhang Wenkang
both addressed the meeting and spoke highly of WHO's achievements
and its cooperative ties with China.
</P>
<P>
WHO's contributions to mankind include a remarkable rise in the
average human life expectancy from 46 years in the 1950s to 65
years in 1994, and the global eradication of smallpox in 1980,
said Zhang Wenkang.
</P>
<P>
Because of a worldwide immunization project targeting children
less than 5 years old, the immunization rate reached 80 percent in
1994, compared with less than 5 percent in 1974, he said.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the organization was initiated by China
and Brazil in 1946. The People's Republic of China regained its
seat in WHO in 1972.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0079 </DOCNO>
