<HEADLINE> World Health Day Observed in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe Tuesday joined the world
in commemorating the World Health Day whose theme this year is
''Safe Motherhood: a Right to Life in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
The theme was chosen after it had been noted that as many as
500,000 people all over the world were dying of child birth
related complications.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the deaths were being recorded in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a function held here to mark the day,
regional-Director of the World Health Organization (WHO) Ebrahim
Samba said Zimbabwe's reproductive health system was doing well
despite different problems which included lack of finance and
resources, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
''Let us encourage our youths to wait for the right age before
they can have babies to avoid unnecessary complications and
deaths,'' said Samba.
</P>
<P>
He said more information about reproductive health needed to
be made accessible to today's youths who experimented with their
lives at times.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, First Lady Grace Mugabe said there was
need to provide the general public with appropriate information
on issues of reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
She said it was sad that mothers and their babies were dying
because of poor health and inadequate care during pregnancy and
childbirth although that could be avoided.
</P>
<P>
''Progress can only be achieved if we join hands in our
concerted efforts both individually and collectively to promote
and support measures and programs aimed at enhancing reproductive
health,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
