<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans to Increase Its Forest Coverage Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China is working out a plan to
increase its forest coverage rate to 19 percent and its urban
green-coverage rate to 35 percent by 2010, Vice Premier Wen Jiabao
said today.
</P>
<P>
Wen, also director of the National Afforestation Committee
(NAC), told the 17th Plenary Meeting of the NAC that the State
Council is drawing up a program which will increase the national
forest coverage rate to 26 percent by the mid-21st century.
</P>
<P>
China's forest coverage rate has risen to 13.9 percent from
12.7 percent in the 1980s and its urban green-coverage rate
increased to 23.8 percent from 19.2 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The vice premier stressed at the meeting that afforestation is
a protracted strategic task which needs the attention of
governments at all levels.
</P>
<P>
The country's forest-coverage project has made remarkable
progress in halting environmental deterioration in recent years,
he said, because of the nationwide voluntary tree-planting drive
and smooth progress of the country's key afforestation projects.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the worsening of the country's ecology has
not been reversed, and rapid industrialization and population
growth will apply even more pressure on resources and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the situation, he said, the government will map
out a long-term afforestation plan and seek approval by the
National People's Congress, China's legislature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
