<HEADLINE> China's Airlines Order Fleet of Passenger Jets for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China will take delivery of 53
airliners in 1998, according to agreements made by the country
with Boeing and Airbus.
</P>
<P>
China Southern Airlines, Air China, China Northwestern Airlines
and China Eastern Air Group will receive most of the aircraft. By
the end of this year, the country's air fleet will include more
than 500 passenger jets. China has 34 air carriers.
</P>
<P>
In January, Air China took the lead in ordering five Boeing
737-800 airliners. Shandong Airlines also placed an order for two
Boeing 737-300 aircraft. This was part of the agreement to
purchase 50 aircraft from Boeing during President Jiang Zemin's
visit to the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
China put 48 airliners into service in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A private air-conditioning enterprise, Hunan Yuanda Group based
in Changsha, bought a jetliner and a helicopter, the first
aircraft purchase by a non-aviation enterprise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
