<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Regulates Enterprise Bond Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBC)
today issued a document on the issuance and transfer of enterprise
bonds in a bid to regulate the enterprise bond market and reduce
risks.
</P>
<P>
The document includes detailed regulations on issuing bonds,
underwriters and underwriting patterns, guaranties, registration
and trust, transfer of names, information release and other
aspects of enterprise bonds.
</P>
<P>
The document gives a detailed list of reports that should be
filed to the PBC by the enterprise applying for bond issuance, and
requires that enterprises must have their guaranty recognized by
the PBC before their bonds are issued.
</P>
<P>
Brokerage houses should be qualified by the PBC before they are
engaged in underwriting enterprise bonds, and the leading
underwriter should publish the proclamation in newspapers
appointed by the PBC at least 10 days before issuance.
</P>
<P>
With ratification from the PBC, enterprises can issue their
bonds by way of either a real-name registered account or
unregistered bonds.
</P>
<P>
Previously, China's enterprise bond market had been
administrated in line with the Regulations Governing Enterprise
Bonds issued by the State Council in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
