<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Railway Passenger Traffic Increases in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Trains in China carried a daily
average of 2.42 million passengers in March, including 649,000
ones over long-distance trips, a rise of 6.7 percent over the same
month last year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the Ministry of Railways, 290,000
TEUs (20-feet equivalent units) of containers of 2.44 million tons
were shipped by train, up 9.7 and 16.1 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The transport of key materials such as iron and steel, gold ore,
metallurgical materials, cement, timber, fertilizer, and grain all
surpassed monthly targets.
</P>
<P>
A total of 27,650 cars of coal were transported by rail, 2,450
cars less than the target, which was blamed on the sluggish coal
market.
</P>
<P>
No railway accidents were reported last month. Fast trains for
freight began operations between Guangzhou and Beijing, Guangzhou
and Shenyang, Keqiao and Chengdu, as well as Ningbo and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Newly appointed Railway Minister Fu Zhihuan said that the
railway sector is expected to generate profits in
three years. To achieve this goal, the ministry will grant railway
enterprises greater management authority and encourage them to
participate in market competition.
</P>
<P>
He said that the speed of trains will be further increased and
the service also will be improved to sharpen railways' competitive
edge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
