<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Hydropower Plant Inaugurated in Laos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A 210-megawatt trans-basin
hydropower plant has been inaugurated in Khammouane province of
Laos after four years of construction, Laos official news agency
KPL reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The project, owned by the Theun-Hinboune Power Co. Ltd, was
jointly launched by Laos, Thailand and the Scandinavian countries,
with an investment of 280 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) acted as the leading
coordinating agency and provided financial and legal advice.
</P>
<P>
The plant is located on the river of Nam Theun, one of the
largest tributaries of the Mekong River in the border area between
Borikhamsay and Khammouane provinces.
</P>
<P>
The dam is 268-meters wide and consists of a 197-meter long
concrete overflow weir, a 71-meter long gated section with two
large radial flood gates, one small radial flood gate, and one
flap gate.
</P>
<P>
The power plant is expected to provide Laos with one billion
U.S dollars in royalties, taxes and dividends during the 30-year
licensed period.
</P>
<P>
The Electricite Du Laos will buy five percent of the
electricity for domestic consumption and the rest will be exported
to Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
