<HEADLINE> China cracks down on Cheating on University Entrance Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Education said
that it will use various means to crack down on rampant cheating in
university entrance examinations.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is quite severe, and the number of crimes is
growing," said Zhang Tianbao, Vice Minister of Education, adding
that there are various cheating methods which are difficult to
discover and that some officials have become involved in the
illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
"This move will help the anti-corruption drive and foster a
good campus style," said Zhang, who is a member of the Central
Commission of the Chinese Communist Party for Discipline
Inspection.
</P>
<P>
Some 15 million people took college entrance exams of different
types last year, with the volume causing difficulties for
officials who sponsor the exams.
</P>
<P>
China's modernization drive emphasizes a university degree. A
university graduate can find a job more easily than those without
college education.
</P>
<P>
However, the country's 1,000 universities cannot provide
sufficient opportunities for all school-age applicants.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said computer technology should be widely used this year
to monitor the exams. He also stressed the need for educational
department workers to be honest.
</P>
<P>
Standardized classrooms for university entrance examinations
must be created, he said, adding that cheating must be dealt with
severely.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to crack down on the fabrication and sale of
false university certificates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
