<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Specialist: Iron, Steel Industry Should Focus on Economic Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- As the world's largest iron and
steel producer, China should maximize economic returns and pursue
technological progress in iron and steel manufacturing while
stablizing its production.
</P>
<P>
In a recently published analysis of this year's domestic iron
and steel market, Zhou Chuandian, former vice minister of China's
defunct Ministry of the Metallurgical Industry, noted it is not
true that the more developed an economy ism the more iron and
steel it needs.
</P>
<P>
With the current economic growth and domestic supply-demand
relationship taken into account, China is projected to consume 100
million tons of steel in 2000, which is approximately the current
annual production.
</P>
<P>
On the surface, according to the metallurgical specialist,
China's present production capacity will be able to satisfy the
demand.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the product structure needs to be
optimized. This finds expression in the imports of many steel
products significant to the national economy, he said, as well as
the excessive production of some goods.
</P>
<P>
Zhou stressed that the only way for steel manufacturers to
achieve sustainable development is to make earnest efforts to
improve the product structure and increase the technology content
in the products.
</P>
<P>
"This is the inevitable path for the healthy development of
China's iron and steel industry." he said.
</P>
<P>
After briefing on the experience and the change of iron and
steel consumption by developed nations, Zhou said economic growth
does not necessarily lead to rising demand for iron and steel
products.
</P>
<P>
That means, he went on to say, that from the early to late
stages of industrialization, with the saturation and gradual
decrease in steel for infrastructure construction, steel
consumption will reach a saturation point and slightly drop.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, technological progress will help bring down
consumption.
</P>
<P>
The use of substitute materials also is increasing. Aluminum
and plastics are taking the place of steel in products ranging
from doors and windows to airplanes and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
The government department in charge of the metallurgy industry
has been aware that the difficulties the industry now encounters
cannot be addressed by mere production expansion or cost reduction.
</P>
<P>
This year's objective of China's metallurgy industry is to
place steel production basically at last year's level, said an
official of the former ministry during a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to turn out 107 million tons of steel in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The official said she believes the industry should make great
efforts to increase the production-sales ratio, readjust the product
structure and reduce stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
Steel manufacturers should be encouraged to make goods with a high
added value which substitute for imports.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show China produced 107.57 million tons of steel in
1997, up 7 percent from 1996. The production volume in January was
8.77 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
