<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes Collection of Ancient Maps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China has published a collection
of 142 ancient maps, dating back to periods from the Warring
States to Qing Dynasty, in both Chinese and English editions.
</P>
<P>
The book, published by the Harbin Map Publishing House, is the
first collection of ancient maps, which introduces the precious
ones among Chinese ancient maps in a systematic way, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The world's oldest map "Zhao Yu Tu", which was discovered in an
ancient tomb of a king in the Warring States (BC.475 - BC.221),
and the world's earliest color map, which was drawn on silk during
Han Dynasty (BC.206 - 24) were published in the book.
</P>
<P>
China, the first country in the world to draw maps, has many
famous ancient maps, which are not only precious cultural relics,
but also important materials for the annals of maps in the world.
</P>
<P>
In order to discover more ancient maps, and have them studied
and published, the State Bureau of Surveying and Mapping and the
State Bureau of Cultural Relics formed a compiling committee in
1986 to prepare for a book of ancient maps.
</P>
<P>
The committee members have collected 3,700 pieces of ancient
maps from all over the country and came to the final design of the
book after careful studies.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the collection has provided valuable materials for
the writing of Chinese surveying and mapping history and
international exchanges in the field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
