<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> edSignal U.S. Firm Shares Merger, Restructuring Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Allied Signal, one of the biggest
suppliers of aerospace and automotive equipment in the United
States, held a seminar here today on acquisitions and mergers,
drawing dozens of senior officials with Chinese ministries and big
companies.
</P>
<P>
Frederic Poses, vice chairman of Allied, briefed participants
on his company's experience in operations management and reform,
and expressed his hope that such lessons could help Chinese
business executives as they tackle the task of making China's
corporations more efficient and profitable.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, Allied has both purchased and sold many businesses,
and more than doubled its profit margins through mergers and
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
"China today is on the threshold of a bold and dramatic new
phase of its evolution as a major economy in the world," Poses
said. "Mergers, acquisitions and restructuring will be effective
measures for China's state-owned enterprises to increase their own
strength and take part in the competitive international market. We
pay close attention to the progress of ongoing mergers,
acquisitions and restructuring in China. China's success in this
area will have a far-reaching influence on Asian, and even world,
economic development."
</P>
<P>
China has been active in mergers, acquisitions and
restructuring in the state-owned sector. Eonomists estimate that
this development will continue and should be speeded up in the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
For China to continue on its path of economic reform, it will
need to carry out mergers, acquisitions and restructuring on a
larger scale and quantity, according to Poses, and "set up
advanced management systems by introducing modern-enterprise
regulations."
</P>
<P>
High ranking officials from the State Economic and Trade
Commission, the State Development Planning Commission and the
Ministry of Science and Technology as well as representatives of
such big companies as FAW (First Automobile Works) Volkswagen, Air
China and China Aviation Industries Corp. attended the seminar.
They said China is ready to learn enterprise reform from developed
nations and to have more information exchanges with those nations.
</P>
<P>
Allied has set up 11 subsidiaries in China, specializing in
manufacturing aerospace and automotive products, chemicals,
plastics and advanced materials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
