<HEADLINE> Ross to Be Back in Middle East Soon: Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian permanent delegate to
the Arab League Mohamed Sobeih said Tuesday that U.S. Mideast
peace envoy Dennis Ross will return to the region soon despite
Israel's attempts to balk such a visit.
</P>
<P>
According to the Middle East News Agency, Sobeih said that if
Ross returns, he would probably carry a written U.S. initiative to
break the year-old deadlock in the Middle East peace-making.
</P>
<P>
The local Arabic-language newspaper Al Ahram reported Tuesday
that U.S. President Bill Clinton would meets with Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright and Ross to decide on dispatching Ross to
the region as a last-ditch effort to exhaust U.S. diplomacy and
maybe announce the U.S. peace plan.
</P>
<P>
Ross ended his latest mission in the region a week ago, failing
to bridge the gap between the Palestinians and Israelis over a
U.S. proposal which reportedly asks Israel to withdraw from 13.1
percent of the West Bank accompanied by security cooperation from
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel flatly rejected the U.S. idea, saying it can accept no
more than 9 percent withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hebron accord signed between the Palestinians
and Israelis last year, Israel should reploy its troops in the
West Bank in three stages that have to be completed in mid 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, which started as a
brainchild of the 1991 Madrid peace conference, have been stalled
for a year over Israeli construction of a new settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem and its long-delayed troop redeployment in the West
bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
