<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Banking Sector Goes Electronic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese banking sector has
used more electronic equipment in recent years to cater to the
need for its modernization.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the banking sector said that computers, networks,
credit cards and other electronic means have had increasing
presence in the sector, largely promoting the business quality and
monetary management capability of banks.
</P>
<P>
So far China's commercial banks have computerized most of their
branches and offices, and over 90 percent of the country's
residential banking business is handled with computers.
</P>
<P>
Networks have been widely adopted in the sector, with
professional banking nets and intranets developing rapidly. The
regional banking network system has been established in many
coastal cities, and the banking-oriented Golden Bridge Network has
set up ports in 24 provinces and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, China started building the national
banking card information exchange network, the core of the Golden
Card Project. This marked that the sector has entered the age of
networks.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector has also developed professional softwares
with high security and powerful functions, basically meeting the
needs of business operations.
</P>
<P>
Credit cards, ATMs and other electronic banking means are also
increasingly popular in China, which greatly expanded banks'
service channels.
</P>
<P>
By now all of China's major banks have opened credit card
business. By the end of 1997, the banks had issued a total of
71.33 million credit cards, with an aggregated trading volume of
over 1.686 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts held that, with the huge number of financial
institutions and the dispersion in their layout, China's banking
sector should further step up its electronics construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
