<HEADLINE> Zhou Enlai's Niece Receives Materials From US Friends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Bingde, a niece of late
Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai, received related materials from
friends of the United States here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
These materials included a copy of the letter written by former
US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger to a committee in the US on
commemorating the centenary of the birth of Premier Zhou, and
overseas press organizations' reports on a concert on February 28,
which was attended by people from both China and the US.
</P>
<P>
Madame Zhou, a member of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference and former Deputy
Director of the China News Service, said that this is "a good
commemoration of Premier Zhou".
</P>
<P>
She expressed her appreciation for the work done by President
of the US-China Association for Promotion of Economy and Trade
(UCAPET) Edward A. Morrison and its Vice-President Luo Zhen.
</P>
<P>
In the letter which was presented to a Museum in Tianjin by
Morrison on April 3, Kissinger spoke highly of Premier Zhou's
life, holding that Premier Zhou had "an extraordinary deft
understanding of statecraft", and he was a man of "exceptional
wisdom, intellect and humor".
</P>
<P>
Morrison said that Zhou Enlai was a pioneer for US-China
relations, and it is of historical significance to keep
Kissinger's letter in the Museum.
</P>
<P>
Madame Zhou noted that in the previous period of time, there
were many activities in China and worldwide to mark the occasion,
believing that Premier Zhou's image will forever remain in the
hearts of Chinese people and of all people around the world.
</P>
<P>
She presented the UCAPET with a set of VCD "The Centenary of
the Birth of Zhou Enlai" commemorating the former Chinese premier
which she sponsored and a book of his poems and some other
writings with madame Zhou as the chief compiler.  
</P>
