<HEADLINE> Sino-Canadian Cooperative Symposium Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of Chinese and Canadian
experts attended a symposium in Beijing today to jointly explore
ways of developing cooperatives in the face of increasing market
competition.
</P>
<P>
Lyle Vanclief, Canada's Minister of Agriculture who is visiting
China, attended the opening ceremony of the symposium which is
being co-sponsored by his ministry and the All-China Federation of
Supply and Marketing Cooperatives (ACFSMC).
</P>
<P>
Experts discussed the challenges and opportunities faced with
cooperatives because of fierce competition in both the domestic
and the international markets, the integration of the world
economy and, especially, the burgeoning of multi-national
companies.
</P>
<P>
Practices in many countries have proved that cooperatives can
only develop through reform, experts said, stressing that
cooperatives deeply rooted in the countryside and the communities
enjoy a unique influence in the development of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Rural residents account for 80 percent of the Chinese
population, and members of Chinese cooperatives make up 80 percent
of the rural population.
</P>
<P>
Mu Li, vice president of ACFSMC, said that China is willing to
learn from foreign countries, he said, expressing his hope that
closer cooperation in personnel exchanges, economy and trade will
be carried out between cooperatives in China and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Vanclief said cooperatives, especially agricultural co-ops,
play an important role in the social and economic life of Canada.
</P>
<P>
He said that cooperation between cooperatives in the two
countries will be beneficial to both, and expressed his conviction
that the present symposium will lay a foundation for further
commercial cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
