<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contaminated Food Causes Health Problems in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Ingestion of food and water
contaminated with disease-causing microorganisms commonly found in
human waste continues to cause major public health problems in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a published report on Tuesday, the Department of Health said
that the 11 confirmed outbreaks, with water as the cause of
infection, had downed at least 1,410 people and killed seven
others in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Most of the outbreaks occurred during the third quarter of last
year, when the long dry spell due to the El Nino phenomenon
started in the country, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the health department, food and waterborne
diseases occur all year round in the Philippines but an increase
in cases is observed during the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
This, the report said, can be attributed to the poor water and
drainage system and poor environmental sanitation.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization said that as much as 80 percent
of diseases in developing countries, including the Philippines,
are caused by the lack of safe water and adequate sanitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
