<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Coup Report Leads to S. A. Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- South African National
Defense Force (SANDF) chief Georg Meiring Monday announced his
resignation amid the controversy about a fraudulent military
intelligence report he gave President Nelson Mandela two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
Barely an hour after Meiring's announcement, Mandela accepted
his request for a premature retirement with effect from May 31.
</P>
<P>
While acceding to the general's request "with regret," Mandela
said his decision was "appropriate and honorable."
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he would name the new SANDF chief after
conferring with his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that SANDF chief of staff, Lieutenant-General
Siphiwe Nyanda, a former commander of the African National
Congress (ANC)'s military wing, Umkhonto we Sizwe (MK), is the
most likely candidate.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his surprising quit, Meiring said: "I have, after
due consideration of all the facts... decided that it would be in
the best interests of the SANDF if I would ask the president to
suspend my contract and allow me to retire on early pension
without prejudice."
</P>
<P>
The 58-year-old general, whose contract ends next April, said
his decision was related to a military intelligence report about
an alleged coup against the government.
</P>
<P>
The report, which Meiring presented personally to Mandela on
February 5, claimed that Nyanda, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela,
Mandela's ex-wife and several other top political figures were
planning to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
It was suspected that by implicating Nyanda in the plot,
Meiring tried to extend his time in power.
</P>
<P>
The report also implicated ousted ANC leader and now
opposition United Democratic Movement (UDM) co-leader, Bantu
Holomisa, and suspended Foreign Affairs official Robert McBride
in the alleged coup. McBride was arrested in Mozambique in March
for alleged gun smuggling.
</P>
<P>
It was later learned that the report had been compiled on
information from a single source who has been found by a court to
be unreliable.
</P>
<P>
Suspicious of the serious allegations, Mandela on March 27
ordered the set-up of a three-member judicial commission, headed
by Chief Justice Ismail Mohammed, to investigate the compilation
and verification of the report as a matter of urgency.
</P>
<P>
After calling senior officials from the SANDF and the
government as witnesses, the commission found last week that
Meiring's handling of the report was flawed and the report had no
substance.
</P>
<P>
The government said the alleged plot was a huge fabrication
and the report was aimed at destabilizing the current democratic
order. It said certain elements in the country were trying to
launch a disinformation campaign as the 1999 general election
draws near.
</P>
<P>
Mandela planned to brief senior security officers and
opposition parties on the commission's findings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, Meiring had reportedly failed to explain
why he gave the report to Mandela without verification and why he
bypassed official intelligence structures, including the
Intelligence Coordinating Committee and Defense Minister Joe
Modise, who would probably have vetoed the report.
</P>
<P>
However, Meiring said Monday that his resignation was not an
acknowledgment that he had acted wrongly or with sinister
motives. He stressed he did so because of the controversy sparked
by the leakage of the report, not its contents.
</P>
<P>
Despite government confirmation that the contents of the
report would not be investigated further, Meiring said such a
probe would be done.
</P>
<P>
He said he was the individual who took the responsibility for
the mistrust unleashed by the inaccurate report.
</P>
<P>
"My position of trust has been unsettled by the report, which
leaves me no choice but to come to this decision... My early
retirement therefore is an effort to restore trust in... the
SANDF," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meiring, who joined the old South African Defense Force in
1959 and became its chief in 1993, was kept on in the post after
the 1994 general election.
</P>
<P>
Perceived as an outspoken "political soldier", Meiring had
publicly clashed repeatedly with the ANC before the 1994
election. The government has been under pressure from politicians
on the left to ditch Meiring since his appointment in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
