<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Securities Investment Funds Warmly Greeted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The first two of China's
long-awaited securities investment funds met with positive
reception today upon listing in the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock
exchanges, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The closed-end Jintai Fund and Kaiyuan Fund opened at
1.45 yuan and 1.37 yuan this morning, and closed at 1.41 yuan and
1.36 yuan. Both funds reported active trading at a turnover of
about eight million units each.
</P>
<P>
"The listing prices fell between the expected range, and are
reasonable," said Chen Jinling, Jintai Fund's manager and
a stock analyst with the Guotai Securities.
</P>
<P>
He said the investors are placing great hopes on the two funds,
citing the facts that the funds were 40 times oversubscribed and
warmly greeted by the investors today.
</P>
<P>
The two funds are hailed as the first two standardized
investment funds set up under the guidelines of the newly-issued
regulations governing securities investment funds. Worth two
billion yuan each, the funds are expected to invest 20 percent
of the capital into bonds, and 80 percent into stocks.
</P>
<P>
The buyers actually entrusted their personal savings to the
professional fund managers through the investment funds, which
promise a much higher yield of about 25 percent, compared to the
less than six percent return on bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike the former investment funds which have much of their
capital mired in real estate and legal person's shares, the new
securities market-targeted investment funds have higher
liquidity, and guarantee more stable returns at fewer risks," said
a stock investor surnamed Zhou, after buying 2,000 units of the
Kaiyuan Fund.
</P>
<P>
Experts have seen much more besides the funds' role as a stable
and secure investment instrument. According to Xiao Zuoji, a noted
Chinese economist, the investment funds will prove to be the most
ideal way for the Chinese securities market to mature and
standardize.
</P>
<P>
"It will attract increasing personal funds into the capital
market, salvaging the fund-thirsty state enterprises. It will also
foster clusters of institutional investors in the Chinese stock
market and bring about fundamental changes there, curbing
overspeculation and irrational investing, and thereby stabilize
the market," explained Xiao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
