<HEADLINE> German Unemployment Rate Drops to 12.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of the unemployed in
Germany dropped to 4.623 million in March, or 12.1 percent of the
total labor force, down from the February reading of 12.6 percent,
the German Labor Office said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The decline in unemployment, which was mainly due to
traditional springtime job gains, was "unexpectedly strong" this
time, said Bernhard Jagoda, president of the Labor Office.
</P>
<P>
However, he also noted that the actual jobless figures still
remained at a post-war record high.
</P>
<P>
When based on seasonally-adjusted figures, the number of the
jobless dropped by 2,000 to 4.414 million in March.
</P>
<P>
While the job situation in the western half of the country
continued to improve, job losses in eastern Germany had not yet
touched bottom, the office said.
</P>
<P>
In western Germany, the jobless total went down by 11,000 to a
seasonally-adjusted 2.958 million in March, while in eastern
Germany, unemployment rose by 9,000 to 1.456 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
