<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Former Israeli Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin met
here this afternoon with former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon
Peres.
</P>
<P>
As an old friend of the Chinese people, Jiang said, Peres has
made "unremitting efforts in promoting the development of the
friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries" when
he served as Israeli prime minister and foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also expressed his appreciation for Peres, who is the
honorary president of the Council for the Promotion of
Israel-China Relations, for his contributions to advancing the
peace process in the Middle East so as to achieve peace between
Israel and its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations, Jiang said that areas for Sino-Israeli
cooperation are "very broad, and with enormous potential."
</P>
<P>
"It's our common wish and is also in the fundamental interests
of the people of both countries to further strengthen the friendly
and mutually beneficial relations between China and Israel," said
Jiang, adding that China hopes to make joint efforts with Israel
to establish a relationship of long stability and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the Middle East, Jiang said that it's a "wise
move" for Israel and the relevant sides of the Middle East to
choose negotiation as a way to solve their conflicts. "It also
accords with the historic trend," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China enjoys friendly relations with all the countries in the
Middle East region, and China will, by exerting its
influence, make great efforts in advancing the peace process of
the region as it has always been doing," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Peres expressed his gratitude to Jiang for the meeting, and
said that China has undergone great change since his visit five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"I'm deeply impressed this time by the social stability, rapid
economic development and the improvement of the living standard in
your country," said Peres.
</P>
<P>
Peres expressed his satisfaction with the development of
Sino-Israeli relations, saying that Israel and China have had
"very good cooperation" in the fields of agriculture, culture and
technology during the past six years.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister said that China's efforts in
advancing the peace process of the Middle East is of "unusual
significance" as China is a permanent member of the Security
Council of the United Nations, and maintains good relations not
only with Israel but also with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Qian Qichen met with Peres on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Peres arrived in Beijing on Friday at the invitation of the
Chinese People's Association for Friendship with Foreign
Countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
