<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hope and Challenge Facing New Century: Shimon Peres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The world is undergoing "very
deep" changes, hope and challenges are still facing the 21st
century, former Israeli prime minister Shimon Peres said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing more than 200 students at the Foreign Affairs
College today, the former Israeli Prime Minister who is
in Beijing for a goodwill visit to China, said that a
number of wars are running down, the world is entering a new age.
</P>
<P>
In the past, all the sources of wealth and strength came from
territories and natural resources, the size of land, which are
related to whether a nation is strong or poor, weak or powerful,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, all the sources of wealth and strength come from
science and technology, added peres, who is also honorary
president of the Council for the Promotion of Israel-China
relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that no matter what color people are or where they
live, the modern opportunities of developing technology and
science and information will enable them to succeed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, markets, due to globalization, are even more
important than countries, and competition is worldwide, he said,
adding that it is necessary to focus on "economic issue", not "on
the importance of land and natural resources".
</P>
<P>
"So, we changed our strategy to make peace with our Arab
neighbors," said Peres, who is the 1994 Nobel Peace Prize winner
along with Yitzhak Rabin and Yasser Arafat. He also called the
Palestine issue "the most complicated issue".
</P>
<P>
For the sake of the younger generation and their future, it
is necessary to advance the Middle East peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the belief that economic exchanges will help
push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Israel-China relations, he said that China is a
very important country in the world and will soon be a power. He
said that China has supported the cause of peace, and that
relationship between the two countries is quite good.
</P>
<P>
Peres arrived here on April 3 and will end his China trip
tomorrow morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spells out Stance at IPU Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese delegation to an
annual conference of the Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU) Tuesday
spelled out China's stance on international issues in Windhoek,
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
"At present, significant and profound changes are continuing
to take place in the international situation, the most noticeable
of which is the accelerated and increasingly obvious movement
toward multipolarization," Li Shuzheng, head of the Chinese
delegation, said.
</P>
<P>
A copy of his speech was available here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Peace and development are the two main themes of today's
world. To seek peace and promote development and cooperation has
become an irresistible trend of the times," said Li, who is vice
chairperson of the Foreign Affairs Committee of China's National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
People all over the world are looking forward to the
establishment of a just and rational new international political
and economic order and longing for lasting peace and development
in the new century.
</P>
<P>
However, she pointed out, Cold War mentality still exists,
regional conflicts caused by ethnic, religious or territorial
disputes still occur from time to time. "The world is still far
from tranquil."
</P>
<P>
She said state-to-state relations should be based on the five
principles of mutual respect for each other's sovereignty and
territorial integrity, mutual non-aggression, non-interference in
each other's internal affairs, equality and mutual benefit, and
peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
"Every country has the right to choose a road of development
in light of its own national conditions. No country should
interfere in the internal affairs of other countries under any
pretext.
</P>
<P>
"This is the political prerequisite for global and regional
security."
</P>
<P>
She said countries should strengthen their mutually beneficial
economic cooperation, level off inequalities and lift
discriminatory policies in economic exchanges and trade so as to
gradually narrow the gap between rich and poor states and attain
common prosperity. "This is the economic foundation for global
and regional security."
</P>
<P>
She said a practical way to realize global and regional
security is for all countries to strengthen consultation and
cooperation in the field of security, to enhance mutual
understanding and trust and seek peaceful settlements to their
differences and disputes.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed "deep concern" over the stalled Middle East peace
process and urged parties concerned to abide by relevant U.N.
resolutions and the "land for peace" principle.
</P>
<P>
She welcomed the peaceful solution to the Iraqi crisis and
urged the strict implementation of the memorandum of
understanding between Iraq and the U.N.
</P>
<P>
China is also concerned about conflicts and unrest in Africa,
she said, pointing out that developed countries should make more
effort to help Africa out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
She called for efforts to maintain the stability of financial
markets so as to ensure a steady economic growth in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
"With relatively weak economic foundation, developing
countries are most vulnerable to the impact and shock of an
adverse financial environment."
</P>
<P>
On human rights, Li said the issue is of universal
significance. But the protection of human rights must be
integrated with the reality of each and every country.
</P>
<P>
She said the Chinese nation has a long tradition of respecting
human dignity and value and today the Chinese people enjoy better
protection of human rights than ever before.
</P>
<P>
She noted that China has acceded to 17 international human
rights instruments. "Last October China signed the International
Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights. We intend to
sign the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights."
</P>
<P>
China has always stood for dialogue on human rights with other
countries to strengthen exchanges and cooperation with other
states and jointly promote the cause of human rights all over the
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Toughen Australian Made Label </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government would
introduce legislation Wednesday in Parliament in a bid to end the
confusion over the term Made in Australia, Australian Customs and
Consumer Affairs Minister Warren Truss said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"All Australians, all consumers, all manufacturers, all
producers will be grateful to have this matter once and for all
resolved," Truss told the Australian parliament.
</P>
<P>
The description Made in Australia will be restricted to items
that are substantially transformed in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The description Product of Australia will be reserved for items
that are 100 percent Australian or as near to it as possible,
Truss said.
</P>
<P>
"The green and gold Australian Made logo will again have the
protection it will need and it will be revitalized," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Industry will be able to use that logo with the knowledge that
it will not be subject to legal challenge and that goods claiming
to be Australian made are indeed products of this country.
</P>
</TEXT>
