<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Hit New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares closed slightly
lower as profit taking offset Wall Street-inspired rises.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 0.8 points lower at 2794.8
after peaking at a record 2806.1 in morning trade.
</P>
<P>
"The market has had a terrific run-up recently and profit
taking would be the main reason for the market to come back in
today's trade," Jack Moss from Shaw Stockbroking said.
</P>
<P>
"Wall Street will give our market direction. If it can hold its
gains and continue to push higher overnight, then our market will
obviously follow in the same vein," he said.
</P>
<P>
In New York overnight, the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed
above 9,000 for the first time Tuesday. It rose 49.82 points to
9033.23.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials index improved 5.7 points to
4813.6, with the banking and building stocks fueling the rise.
</P>
<P>
ANZ led the improvement with a 25 cent jump in trade of 6.6
million shares, Commonwealth improved 14 cents, National Australia
added 4.2 cents and Westpac was steady.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 7.0 points to 1181.1.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto fell 18.6 cents while BHP lost five. BHP announced
Tuesday that outgoing managing director John Prescott's
resignation will take effect from the end of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The gold index rose 4.4 points to 1305.8 as the bullion price
fell 0.80 cents to 308.70 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 335 million shares worth 989.03 million
Australian dollars (652.75 million dollars) with falls of 616
beating falls of 555. 
</P>
