<HEADLINE> Ugandan Herbalists to Give Lectures in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan herbalists will give
lectures to academic staff and students in Makerere University,
the country's major institution of high learning, The New Vision
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Karemire Turyagenda of Chemistry Department of
Makerere University told a workshop last Thursday that local
herbalists are to be involved in teaching the students of
Makerere and other universities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Makerere University is the most prestigious one in the country
and has trained many leaders and scientists such as Kenyan
president Daniel arap Moi and Julius Kambarage Nyerere, former
president of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the herbalists have more knowledge in certain
medicinal plants than me," the professor told the workshop aimed
at conserving medicinal plants and biodiversity. He urged the
local herbalists to publish their work.
</P>
<P>
Local herbalists accumulated abundant experience in thier
practice. But they have few opportunities to circulate their
knowledge. The professor assureed that the intellectual right of
the herbalists who promulgates their works would be protected.
</P>
<P>
Ogwal Okeng, a local pharmacologists, said he had learned much
from traditional healers through his research.
</P>
<P>
At least 80 local patients turn to traditional medicine for
help, some experts estimated.
</P>
<P>
Nasani Kiranda Mubiru, Director of the Research Laboratory of
Makerere University, told the workshop that Ugandan traditional
medicine is effective for many diseases. He asserted that local
traditional medicine "will be the medicine of the next
millennium".
</P>
<P>
Uganda will soon get equipment to extract medicine from its
herbs on the industrial level. "The venture will cost at least
900,000 U.S. Dollars, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has at least 1,600 known medicinal herbs and a long
history of developing its traditional medicine. But the medicine
knowledge is only spread from a master to his apprentice in a
traditional way.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the National Association of Traditional
Herbalists has launched seminars to train traditional medicine
men publicly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
