<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar fell
Tuesday in response to a slip in the price of gold and on the
speculation of an easing in monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Gathering expectations that the Reserve Bank of Australia could
cut the official cash rate Wednesday following its monthly board
meeting Tuesday was the concern behind the market.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has in the past sometimes changed the level of
the official cash rate the morning after its board meeting.
</P>
<P>
"If they do cut tomorrow and you are hedged that way, certainly
you are going to gain," traders said.
</P>
<P>
The official cash rate currently stands at 5.00 percent. The
Reserve Bank of Australia last eased the rate by 50 basis points
on July 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed trading Tuesday at 65.70 U.S. cents, from
66.06 late Monday.
</P>
<P>
ANZ head of foreign exchange sales John Reedyk said the
currency had been unable to sustain Monday's gains which were made
on the back of a stronger gold price.
</P>
<P>
A rise in the Japanese yen which provided the faltering local
unit with some support was overshadowed by the rate cut talk.
</P>
<P>
Also, traders noted limited regional activity with holidays in
Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended the local session at 88.07 from
88.94 against Japanese yen, and at 1.2081 from 1.2175 against
German marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
