<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Write-Off Process of Poor Countries Too Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, ADpril 7 (Xinhua) -- The African Forum and Network on
Debt and Development (AFRODAD) has charged that the process of
debt write-off of the Highly Indebted Poor Countries (HIPCS) is
going much slower than it hase originally been anticipated, the
Zambian newspaper Financail Mail reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The AFRODAD said that this raises questions of whether or not
the debt write-off initiative will secure sustainable debt levels
for Africa's HIPCS.
</P>
<P>
It said that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) remains the
largest single creditor and as such the IMF needs to be persuaded
to take its responsibility by ushering in more grant financial
resources throught the HIPCS enhanced structural adjustment
facility trust fund.
</P>
<P>
"The World Bank and the IMF still remain closed to
participation of primary stakeholders in the formulation of debt
sustainability analysis in the different African countries in
spite of their 'participation policies'," it said.
</P>
<P>
Africa's debt have reached some 315 billion U.S. Dollars and
its implications is now somewhat widely understood, according to
AFRODAD.
</P>
<P>
The debt problem poses a threat to the structural changes and
a sustainable solution is needed to ensure that the debt problem
does not arise again and current process and borrowing is not
creating a new form of debt crisis, said the organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
