<HEADLINE> Ceasefire Accord on Bougainville to Be Signed: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer Tuesday said a formal ceasefire between
Bougainville rebels and the Papua New Guinea (PNG) government
could be signed later this month.
</P>
<P>
"The ceasefire arrangement is almost certain to be signed in
Arawa on Bougainville towards the end of this month," Downer told
the Australian parliament in Canberra.
</P>
<P>
Rebels on the island announced independence from PNG in 1990
and later the war between the rebels and PNG government troops
broke out.
</P>
<P>
A truce on Bougainville was agreed upon earlier this year after
talks in New Zealand. A New Zealand-led Truce Monitoring Group has
since helped to keep peace on the island, supported by Australian
Defense Force personnel.
</P>
<P>
Downer said "a final date is yet to be determined but certainly
before the end of this month and I very much hope to be present
myself for the signing, given the role Australia has played in
helping to facilitate this process."
</P>
<P>
Australia has pledged 87 million U.S. dollars in aid to restore
essential services and infrastructure on the shattered island.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Australia could take much of the credit for ending
the war between secessionist rebels on the island and Papua New
Guinea government forces and their allies on Bougainville.
</P>
</TEXT>
