<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Makes No Progress in Regulating Currency Trading: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) has not shown any progress in efforts to regulate
currency trading, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the IMF has promised to study Malaysia's proposal on
the matter, it has yet to make any suggestion, Mahathir told
reporters in Jitra in the northern state of Kedah, when asked to
comment on the latest development in Malaysia's proposal to
regulate currency trading following the financial crisis in the
region since last July.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know why...so long as the currency fluctuates,
currency traders will make profits," he was quoted by the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that if Malaysia's currency was stable, currency
traders would not reap profits, and that was why they (currency
traders) were not interested in restoring the ringgit's value.
</P>
<P>
"Although the World Bank, IMF and all parties recognize our
strong economic fundamentals the ringgit still depreciates," he
said, adding the currency traders had their own views (on the
country's economic fundamentals) and were not swayed by statements
from the World Bank or anybody.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether his government would take further measures,
Mahathir said "I don't know what measures...we have done what we
should but the ringgit is still weak."
</P>
<P>
The local unit is now worth about 3.70 ringgit to one U.S.
dollar against 2.50 ringgit to the dollar nine months ago before
the financial crisis hit the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
