<HEADLINE> Large number of Kenyan Civil Servants Asked to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
reportedly asked some 19,500 civil servants to retire by the end
of June this year, the Kenya Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted a source at the office of the
president as saying that the Directorate of Personnel Management
(DPM) had started working out modalities on how to implement the
retirement scheme in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
The retirement scheme affecting all cadres under the Public
Service Commission was part of the conditions given by the World
Bank for the release of development aid to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Under a voluntary early retirement scheme, the civil service
workforce amounting to some 500,000 has already reduced by some
86,112 staff and more than 100 million Dollars were spent for the
scheme, the source at the presidential office was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the DPM said the retirement scheme was too costly
for the government, noting that "unless the finances sought from
World Bank to fund the exercise were released, the program may
stall".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae told a
workshop on Monday that there was a need to trim government
departments which, he said, had led to unnecessary increase in
expenditures on administration and staffing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
