<HEADLINE> Arab Leaders to Visit Lebanon over Israeli Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid are planing
separate visits to Lebanon for talks with the country's leaders on
the Israeli proposed conditional withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Daily Star newspaper said Tuesday that Mubarak phoned
his Lebanese counterpart Elias Hrawi on Monday night to express
his unwavering support for Beirut over its stance on the Israeli
offer, and said he was contemplating a visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Israeli Cabinet for the first time in two
decades formally approved, with conditions, the United Nations
resolution 425, which calls for Israeli unconditional and
immediate withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It linked the implementation of the resolution with negotiated
security arrangements with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, the main power broker in the region, have
firmly rejected the offer, saying the resolution asks Israel to
leave Lebanon without any conditions, and therefore the strings
attached in the offer are unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also accused Israel of attempting through
the offer to separate the Lebanese track from Syria in the peace
talks with Israel and instigating strife inside Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria has been asking Israel to withdraw its troops from the
Golan Heights, a strategic plateau captured by Israel in the 1967
Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
The joint stance taken by the two countries has won support
from the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid informed the Lebanese Foreign Ministry on Monday
that he will visit Lebanon and Syria on Thursday to hold talks
with the leaders of the two countries in order to draft a joint
response to the Israeli offer, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Israel now occupies a 1,200-square-kilometer area in south
Lebanon with the claimed aim of protecting its northern villages
and towns from Lebanese guerrillas cross-border attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
