<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Foreign Exchange Inflows Hard to Sustain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's foreign exchange inflows
in the first quarter of 1998 has been too little to sustain the
foreign exchange market, hence the continued depreciation of the
Kwacha against other currencies.
</P>
<P>
From January to March 20, inflows to the Bank of Zambia (BOZ),
the central bank, amounted to merely 3.921 million U.S. Dollars,
of which only 1.676 million Dollars came from donors and 2.245
million dollars from non-government sources, mainly
non-traditional exports and retentions.
</P>
<P>
BOZ statistics last week showed that the inflows have
been very minimal mainly due to reduced earnings from copper
sales, the biggest foreign exchange earner in Zambia, and
non-inflow of donor funds allegedly because of disagreement on
good governance issue.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the Zambian government released 81.514 million
Dollars in the past months to service its external debt which
totals 7.2 billion Dollars, and to support other government
expenditure as well as the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has released 28.8 million Dollars (mainly in
last January) onto the foreign exchange market to beef up the
dwindling market so as to save the Kwacha from further
butchering.
</P>
<P>
This move, however, did nothing to change the situation as the
Kwacha continued depreciating from 1,330 last September to 1,700
Kwacha against the Dollar at present.
</P>
<P>
The continued dwindling in foreign exchange inflows may have
an adverse effect on the fragile economy as this may erode the
purchasing power of the Kwacha that may in turn force
manufacturers to push up prices of their goods, which will bring
a chain reaction in price spiral.
</P>
<P>
This, some analysts indicated, will cause high inflation rate
and economic stagnation.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the depreciation of the Kwacha to the
withholding of foreign exchange by donors due to displeasure with
the Zambian government over the imposition of four-month state of
emergency after last year's foiled military coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Stock Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Component Stock Index on the
Shenzhen Stock Exchange finished at 4,204.73 today, down 16.27
points from the previous session, according to the Guangfa
Securities Co. Ltd.
</P>
