<HEADLINE> Zambia's Polyester Cotton Yarn to Be Exported to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has been granted derogation
on the exportation of polyester cotton yarn into the European
Union with previous requirements regarding rules of origin now
waived.
</P>
<P>
The derogation stipulates that polyester-cotton yarn
originating from Zambia between June 1 this year and February 20
in the year 2002 will be exempted from the rules of origin
contained in the Lome Convention, reported Financial Mail on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Export Board of Zambia spokesman
Leonard Simwanda as saying that this means that the previous
requirements on the rules of origin contained in the Lome
Convention will now be waived on Zambia's exports.
</P>
<P>
The amount exempted over the specified period will be 3,500
tons per year.
</P>
<P>
The EU/ACP (Asian Caribbean and Pacific group) Lome
Convention, which expires in the 2000, is the largest trade
agreement helping the developing countries to expand their
exports through preferential access to the EU markets.
</P>
<P>
But the impending expiry of the convention has aroused debate
as to the future of these countries, especially on what the new
agreement will be like and weather the developing countries will
lose this advantage they had been granted by the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
