<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bankruptcy Increases to Record High in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Bankruptcy filings in the
United States last year increased by 19.1 percent to a record high
of more than 1.4 million, according to the American Bankruptcy
Institute (ABI).
</P>
<P>
The record number was driven by consumer filings, which
accounted for 96 percent of all filings in 1997. Last year,
personal and family insolvencies, or non-business filings, hit a
record of more than 13.5 million, up 20 percent from 1996. By
contrast, business bankruptcy rose by only 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the ABI, an organization dedicated to
research and education on matters related to insolvency, one of
every 70 households in the United States filed for bankruptcy last
year, up from one in every 82 households a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the field noted that consumers are filing for
bankruptcy protection from their creditors in record numbers
despite low unemployment, tame inflation and strengthening family
income.
</P>
<P>
The trend departs from historical norms, which saw bankruptcy
rise and fall in sync with the business cycle. An analysis
prepared by a Washington D.C. attorney blames the shift on a
pro-debtor rewrite of the bankruptcy law in 1978.
</P>
<P>
The nation's states differ widely in their approach to
shielding a debtor's personal assets from creditors. Some are very
stingy, while others allow debtors to protect huge fortunes,
including multimillion-dollar residences.
</P>
<P>
Congress is looking into complaints by many creditors that the
bankruptcy system needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
But debtors and their sympathizers reject their claim,
asserting that families should not be turned into the streets.
</P>
<P>
The battle line for the two sides are drawing around two
provisions in the law, Chapter 7 and Chapter 13 of the Bankruptcy
Code.
</P>
<P>
Chapter 7 is an option used in about 70 percent of the cases,
in which the debtor converts most household assets to cash. The
money is used to reimburse creditors in accordance with the
strength of their claims, leaving the debtor free to launch a
fresh and unencumbered start on life. But in most cases the
debtors have almost no assets bearing any cash value.
</P>
<P>
Chapter 13 allows debtors to retain their assets in return for
paying off creditors from future earnings in accordance with a
court-approved plan that usually remains in effect for three to
five years.
</P>
<P>
A bill now moving through the Senate would give courts a greater
role in determining which chapter should apply to debtors seeking
bankruptcy protection from creditors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
