<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Spending Billions of Yuan on Waste Water Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A second phase of a waste water
treatment program, which is expected to cost 6.3 billion yuan (790
million US dollars), has begun in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
A 40.5-km-long pipeline will be laid in the upper reaches of
the Huangpu River, the city's main drinking water source, to take
in waste water from fowl farms, industrial enterprises and
residential housing.
</P>
<P>
Three large waste water treatment plants will be built along
the pipeline and a waste processing plant on the coast of the
East China Sea.
</P>
<P>
About 20 km of the pipeline have been laid. By the end of next
year, 170 tons of waste water will be treated each day, allowing
the city to treat half of its waste water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
