<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Export Fuel in 1999: Oil Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- As Nigerians have been suffering
from the acute fuel scarcity for weeks, the Ministry of Petroleum
Resources said Monday that the country is expected to export refined
oil products beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing in the capital Abuja, Minister Chief Dan
Etete said this could become possible as the federal government
has embarked on a program to solve the problems besetting the oil
sector once-and-for-all.
</P>
<P>
The recurrent crippling fuel crisis in Nigeria is mainly
attributed to the lack of maintenance of the country's four
aging refineries.
</P>
<P>
But the minister pledged that the refineries would have been
brought back to their normal production level by the time the
present administration leaves office in October this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry "are doing everything possible" to deal with the
persisting fuel scarcity, he said, adding "What we need is the
cooperation of all patriotic Nigerians".
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that Etete was blaming for the problem on
"unpatriotic elements who indulge in hoarding and diversion of
the product (fuel)".
</P>
<P>
Vandals who are tampering with the fuel pipelines were making
the situation worse, said the minister, who just returned from
the emergency meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
On the outcome of the OPEC extra-ordinary meeting in Vienna,
he reiterated that the cut in Nigeria's daily quota by 125,000
barrels to 2.01 million barrels would not affect this year's
budget, a clear hint that the government will not review down the
budget as widely speculated.
</P>
<P>
As Africa's leading oil producer and exporter, Nigeria based
this year's budget revenue on the export of oil at 17 U.S.
Dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
When the budget was being drawn, exigencies such as the
present cut in production and the sharp fall in oil prices were
taken into consideration, Etete explained.
</P>
<P>
He said Nigeria is not panicking or in a panicky situation
because of the reduction, while assuring that it has nothing to
do with the domestic fuel consumption.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that this year's budget is not adversely affected,
Etete said he and Finance Minister Chief Anthony Ani have been in
close consultation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
