<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Urges For Greater Efforts for Women's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) Tuesday called for greater efforts to protect women from
childbirth illnesses and other pregnancy-related complications.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF, in a report released here, said tens of thousands
of women across Asia die of childbirth illnesses and injuries each
year, while millions of others suffer from painful and often
life-long disabilities.
</P>
<P>
The report was timed to mark this year's "World Health Day"
which falls on April 7, with the theme of "Pregnancy Is Special:
Let's Make It Safe."
</P>
<P>
The report noted that pregnancy and childbirth are the leading
causes of death, diseases and disabilities among women of
reproductive age in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
While one in every 16 women in Africa risks dying from
pregnancy-related complications, one in 65 women risks the same in
Asia, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Asian countries with high maternal mortality rates include
Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Indonesia and the Philippines, according
to the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
"Making motherhood safe requires more than good quality
reproductive health services. Women must be empowered, and their
human rights -- including their right to good quality services and
information during and after pregnancy and childbirth -- must be
guaranteed," said the report.
</P>
<P>
Of all health statistics monitored by the WHO, maternal
mortality is one with the largest discrepancy between developed
and developing countries, said Dr. E. B. Doberstyn, WHO
representative in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said that while infant mortality is almost seven times
higher in developing countries, maternal mortality is on an
average 18 times higher.
</P>
<P>
Estimations based on the latest statistics of the WHO show that
while the rate of maternal deaths is 480 women per 100,000 live
births in developing countries, it is 27 women per 100,000 live
births in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
To help reduce the gap in women's health between various
countries, the WHO planned to launch a mass campaign to build
awareness and support for "safe motherhood" later Tuesday in
Washington, where experts will outline social and economic
implications of this global problem, according to WHO officials
based in Bangkok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
