<HEADLINE> China to Export Imperial Food to Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- This year, China will start
exporting a kind of millet used just for tributes to emperors
to Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The Gulong millet, which is a unique product of northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province, is claimed to be nutritious,
digestible and good for health. Local people call it the "food of
longevity".
</P>
<P>
The product has long been used as a gift for relatives by
local people, because it was grown in a small area with low yields.
</P>
<P>
The Zhaoyuan County government and the Jitai Company of
neighboring Jilin Province will form a joint venture to produce
the millet, according to Tian Fengchun, the county magistrate.
</P>
<P>
They will spend 27 million yuan on the construction of a
6,600-ha farm, an irrigation system and a processing plant with an
annual production capacity of 20,000 tons. All the products will
be exported to Hong Kong and Southeast Asian countries from
October on, Tian said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
