<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Calls for Cut in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae has called for a 20 percent annual cut in civil service
salaries and allowances, local press reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a workshop on economic performance and public
sector management held here on Monday, Nyachae said the
government cannot afford to meet the wage bill of over 1.05
billion U.S. Dollars every year, or 39 percent of ordinary
revenues.
</P>
<P>
He noted that last year's wage agreement with teachers, who
were granted salary increases of up to 200 percent over three
years, was not sustainable.
</P>
<P>
The national budget and the economy will feel the crunch in
the next three years as the government was expected to meet
higher teachers' pay and allowances in five phases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae stressed the need to trim government departments which
led to poor coordination and an unnecessary increase in
expenditures on administration and staffing.
</P>
<P>
The proposed cut in government departments is shall help to
reduce government expenditure on salaries and allowances by 20
percent a year, which will release about 210 million Dollars for
redeeming domestic debt, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's domestic debt increased from 1.8 billion Dollars by
June last year to 2.3 billion Dollars by the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae stated that the Public Investment Program for 1998/99
contained 1,226 on-going projects and 441 new ones which needed
eight billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
There were no enough resources available to complete even 20
percent of the on-going projects in the portfolio within the next
three years, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae attributed the current economic strain in Kenya to
withholding of foreign aid and rampant corruption in government
departments.
</P>
<P>
"When the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF)
program lapsed in August 1997, we lost a direct IMF
(International Monetary Fund) loan of 175 million Dollars," he
said.
</P>
<P>
A more serious consequence of the suspension of ESAF program
was the sudden jump of Treasury Bill interest rates from 19 to 27
percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
As a result of this development, he said, the expenditure on
domestic interest increas d by about 30 percent compared to the
budgeted levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
