<HEADLINE> Knowledge Economy, China's Choice For Progress Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Knowledge economy has been widely
considered a choice for a developing country like China for
progress and modernization.
</P>
<P>
In a signed article in today's "Guangming Daily", He Chuanqi,
an economist from the Chinese Academy of Sciences, noted that
China will have to tide over three stages featuring domination of
industrialization with equal emphasis on combination of
industrialization and knowledge economy if it wants to be part of
the information age.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage, there must be a strategy of using science
and education to make build a prosperous China, and improving
China's inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
In the second stage, accelerated application of information and
knowledge in the industrial and agricultural sectors is necessary
for modernization, and an improved information infrastructure and
an increased number of enterprises in it.
</P>
<P>
In the third stage, political, legal, economic, and social
systems that are compatible with the needs of the information age
need to be built.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a group of specialist-entrepreneurs
in east China's Zhejiang Province have been praised as harbingers
in the age of knowledge economy.
</P>
<P>
They include Ke Chuankui, General Manager of Hangzhou's Jiuyuan
Genetic Engineering Corporation, which has developed medicine for
increasing the number of white blood cells, and Mao Jiangsen, of
the Chinese Academy of Sciences, who is CEO of the Pukang Company,
which makes hepatitis A vaccine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
