<HEADLINE> China Collected 26 Billion Yuan in Personal Income Taxes in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China collected 26 billion yuan in
personal income taxes in 1997, accounting for 3.44 percent of the
country's total industrial and commercial taxes.
</P>
<P>
According to today's "Economic Daily" report, the provinces of
Guangdong, Jiangsu, Liaoning and the municipalities of Shanghai
and Beijing provided 3.55, 1.52, 1.49, 2.94 and 2.87 billion yuan
in personal income taxes last year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The five greatest annual increases in personal income taxes
were reported in Tibet, Qinghai, Anhui, Yunnan and Inner Mongolia,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region collected 395 million yuan
last year, up 29.4 percent from 1996. 
