<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Southeast Asia May Face Worst </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asians are beset with the
nightmare of forest fires, which have eaten up tens of thousands
of hectares of forests in Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia and
Thailand since January, and led to severe air pollution in the
region.
</P>
<P>
This year's forest fires in Southeast Asia could be "one of the
greatest ecological disaster of the millennium," if the fires
could not be contained quickly, Klaus Topfer, executive director
of the U.N. Environment Program, warned recently.
</P>
<P>
Actually, such a warning is becoming a reality, as forest fires
are continuing and smog is worsening in most Southeast Asian
nations, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Although fires have been reportedly under control in Thailand,
in the Philippines, the government is still seeking assistance
from Australia, Canada and the United States in putting out forest
fires on the island of Palawan, the Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Forest fires have hit eight provinces in the Philippines from
January to April, and a total of 22,594 hectares of forest lands
were destroyed, according to the National Disaster Coordinating
Council.
</P>
<P>
The affected provinces include Benguet, Oriental Mindoro,
Palawan, Negros Occidental, Zamboanga del Norte, Davao del Norte,
Davao Oriental and Davao del Sur.
</P>
<P>
However, other reports said that in Palawan alone, about 30,000
hectares of forest were damaged by the fires, which started in
mid-March by farmers practicing the traditional slash and burn
method.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Malaysia is no better. Fires have been burning
in the Malaysian state of Sarawak, where at least 1,000 hectares
of forest were lost. The culprits are local timber companies
diversifying into palm oil, in order to take advantage of buoyant
prices.
</P>
<P>
Compared with other Southeast Asian countries, the disaster in
Indonesia is the worst in the region. Since mid-January, forest
fires in Sumatra and East Kalimantan came back. The latest
official figures show that fires in East Kalimantan have destroyed
138,030 hectares of forest, plantation and bushland in the last
three months.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the real damage to Southeast Asian countries is
not only the loss of thousands upon thousands of hectares of
forest, but the haze which is affecting environment of the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Southeast Asia May Face Worst </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Last year, the haze from Indonesia's fire affected Southeast
Asian nations' industrial production, tourism, air transportation
and fishing, and cost the region 1.384 billion U.S. dollars, the
World Wide Fund for Nature estimated in a February report.
</P>
<P>
This year, the haze has already affected disaster areas of
Southeast Asian countries. In Miri, an oil-town in Malaysia's
Sarawak State, nearly 200 schools have been closed indefinitely
since March 30 when the air pollution index surged past critical
levels to 620, as a reading over 500 is considered very hazardous.
</P>
<P>
Officials blamed the haze on local fires and fires in
Indonesia's East Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
In Mindanao, the Southern Philippines, people have also
experienced the haze from local fires and Indonesian forest fire.
</P>
<P>
But, experts said, this year's major haze threat will still
come from Indonesia because the situation there is far more
critical than in any other Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
They said that for the moment, the northeast monsoon is blowing
the smoke away from Indonesia's northern neighbors, but everything
will change when the southwest monsoon begins in July.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to avert one of the century's worst ecological
disaster, environment ministers of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) met in Brunei last Saturday and discussed a
package of measures to combat smog from Indonesian forest fires.
</P>
<P>
The ministers proposed that fires in East Kalimantan be
contained rather than any attempt made to put them out.
</P>
<P>
They planned to establish two special fire-fighting units for
Kalimantan, Sumatra and Riau, the hotbeds of the fire which has
sent smoke over much of the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed to set up a central revolving fund
from regional and international contributions.
</P>
<P>
However, these measures may far from enough to contain fires in
Indonesia, since the country has limited financial resources due
to an economic crisis and its neighbors could hardly provide
assistance when they are also being hit by the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
