<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Private Airlines Goes Into Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's third private air
company, GMG Airlines, went into operation following inauguration
ceremony on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newly-floated private company is engaged in domestic air
service with 37-seater Canadian aircraft Dash-8.
</P>
<P>
It will operate flights to the country's second largest city of
Chittagong, 224 kilometers southeast of Dhaka, Sylhet, 208
kilometers northeast of the capital and Jessore, 146 kilometers
southwest of here, with two Dash-8 aircraft, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
The involvement of the private sector in air services "will not
only meet the increasing demand of the people, but also create a
healthy atmosphere of competition," Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina
said at the launching ceremony at the Dhaka International Airport.
</P>
<P>
"We have formulated a policy with lucrative incentives for
private air transportation," she said. "The private sector is also
taking part in plane, helicopter and international cargo
services."
</P>
<P>
Besides, she said, the government has taken steps for
modernization and expansion of Dhaka International Airport to
accelerate economic activities.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister asked private airlines to extend their
services under the rules and regulations of the civil aviation
authority. "You will have to maintain service in line with the
demand of the people and their capacity."
</P>
<P>
She also called for ensuring flight security in accordance with
the "Standard and Recommendation Practice" of the International
Civil Aviation Organization. 
</P>
