<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Brace for More Palestinian Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police are bracing for
renewed violence Tuesday after they shot dead a Palestinian youth
overnight at a checkpoint in northern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian was passing the Kalandiya checkpoint driving a
car suspected of being stolen in Israel when Israeli border police
ordered him to stop.
</P>
<P>
Police said the man ignored the order and accelerated to
escape. The police gave a chase. The car hit two police cars
before the police opened fire and killed the driver. Another
passenger inside the car was not hurt and escaped on foot in the
direction of the West Bank city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Following the man's death, local Palestinian residents rioted
by throwing stones at the Israeli soldiers and policemen.
Jerusalem police chief Yair Yitzhaki, who came to the site to
inspect, was lightly hurt by stones and was treated on the spot.
</P>
<P>
The police said they are investigating the incident to
determine if the killed man was involved in terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli woman passenger was lightly injured Monday night
when a bus she was riding came under stone attacks by Palestinians
at the Damascus Gate to the Old City of East Jerusalem. Another
bus was also attacked by stones.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of major Jewish holiday of Passover, extra security
forces have been deployed at border crossings and public places
to brace for more Palestinian violence and possible terror
attacks by the militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas).
</P>
<P>
Hamas has vowed to avenge the death of its bombmaker Muhei
Eddine Sharif, whose body was found inside a car exploded in
Ramallah on March 29.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority announced Monday that its
investigation showed that Sharif was killed by fellow militants in
an internal feud, but Hamas rejected the conclusion and continued
to hold Israel responsible for Sharif's killing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
