<HEADLINE> China to Establish System to Monitor Crust Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China will set up a nationwide
crust movement monitoring system to provide data on earthquakes,
today's People's Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Using some new high-tech developments like satellite and laser
monitoring, Chinese scientists will be able to get information
that helps them improve earthquake predictions, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The system, which is a key national project in the Ninth
Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), will cost 135 million yuan (16.2
million US dollars) and be completed in 2001.
</P>
<P>
It will be built by the State Seismology Bureau, the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, the State Bureau of Surveying and Mapping,
and the PLA's Surveying and Mapping Bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
