<HEADLINE> China's Qaidam Basin Looking At Technology Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China's 250,000-square-meter Qaidam
Basin in Qinghai Province, which is rich in salt, oil and gas,
nonferrous metals, and metals, is developing high added-value
products.
</P>
<P>
Reserves of 11 of the 120 discovered minerals in the basin are
the largest in the country, and some enterprises there have
improved technology to develop more high added-value mineral
products, according to Wang Hengsheng of the provincial Social
Science Academy.
</P>
<P>
He says that salt processed in the basin sells well in China
and in 10 foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Potash Fertilizer Plant has got overseas investment
and expects to produce 800,000 tons of potash fertilizer
annually. In 1992, it produced 200,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Technology has played an important role in increasing annual
production capacity and profits, Wang says, and that the Qaidam
Basin will help the economic revitalization of the western regions
in the country. 
</P>
