<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Industry Asked To Get Out Of Small Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China's Statistics Bureau (SSB)
has suggested that state-owned industry should get out of less
important, small industries where it has no expertise and focus on
major areas instead.
</P>
<P>
State industries have been running in the red for more than
three years in 240 small businesses, mainly in small-scale,
labor-intensive production, according to a report by a SSB
industrial restructuring group.
</P>
<P>
Areas that should be dropped are photographic equipment,
container manufacturing, feather processing, glasses, weight
measurement, silk fabrics, and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
China has 606 small industrial areas, 382 of which were running
in the red at the end of 1996, and in the 240 areas, state-owned
businesses contribute only 16.3 percent of production.
</P>
<P>
The project group has suggested that state industry not get out
of 40 small areas like coal gas, salt, mining machinery, and
optical equipment, at least for the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
