<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers' Living Expenses Continue to Go Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The cost of food, durable goods,
and clothing for China's farmers are expected to rise about 8
percent this year and sales of home appliances and building or
decoration materials will help boost rural markets, according to a
recent survey of the All China Supply and Marketing Cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey of 3,878 rural households, average cost
of consumer goods will be 1,200 yuan, up 7.8 percent from last
year.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Hebei, Xinjiang, and Fujian will spend 20 percent
more than last year, and farmers in Hunan, Tianjin and Inner
Mongolia will spend about 10 percent more.
</P>
<P>
Demand for better quality food will grow, while staple foods
like grain and edible oils will remain stable, but fast foods,
bottled drinks, beer, and children' food will go up, the survey
shows.
</P>
<P>
Durable goods have good prospects, and demand for home
appliances and telecommunications products will continue to grow
16.9 percent and 32.4 percent respectively, and spending for
ready-made garments will go up a great deal.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in economically-developed areas will spend more on
decorating their houses, while farmers in central and western
parts of China will put more emphasis on housing construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Residents Shun Commitment to Cremation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Only a dozen people signed their names on a banner calling for
using paper coffins and cremation outside the city's crematory and
cemetery on April 5, the traditional day for Chinese to sweep the
graves of their ancestors and pay respect for the dead, according
to Monday's Yangcheng Evening News that arrived here today.
</P>
<P>
The name-signing activity was initiated by students from the
South China University of Science and Engineering who came to the
cemetery before 8 a.m. and put up the slogan "saving wood and
protecting environment."
</P>
<P>
By noon time, April 5, a little more than ten people including
a boy of six signed the banner. More than 300,000 people visited
the cemetery that day, the most in recent ten years, according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The students also did a survey among 2,000 people, asking their
opinions on cremation. The result showed 83 percent of those
surveyed were in favor of cremation while only 10 percent showed
disapproval.
</P>
<P>
But even cremation supporters did not like the idea of making
commitment of any sort, such as signing their names. An old man
said he was in favor of cremation but would not practise it himself.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is known for its sticking to the old practice of
burying people and for its funeral rituals. The cremation rate in
the province is estimated at 23.5 percent, or 10 percentage points
lower than the nation's average. In several cities, the rate is
below 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a move to save its farmland by changing some traditional
funeral practices, the province has decided to halt the practice
of burying the dead starting this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
