<HEADLINE> Dhaka' FDI Expected to Reach 3b Dollars This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The foreign direct investment (FDI)
in Bangladesh may reach 3 billion U.S. dollars this year, media
reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Chairman of the Board of Investment (BOI) Farooq
Sobhan stated this while speaking at a meeting of the
France-Bangladesh Chamber of Commerce and Industry held in Dhaka
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government had already declared six areas as
the "thrust sectors," the BOI chief said referring to investment
prospects in this South Asian country.
</P>
<P>
One of the world's biggest cement manufacturers, Lafarge of
France, would set up a cement factory at Sylhet, 208 kilometers
northeast of here, with an annual production capacity of 1.2
million tons, he stated, adding that an agreement on the
240-million-dollar project is likely to be signed soon.
</P>
<P>
The government's investment thrust was currently focused on
infrastructure development, power generation, road and highway
construction, textile sector, computer and data processing, and
leather sector, he told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The BOI chief said French businessmen could invest in joint
venture projects, while Malaysian investors had shown keen
interest in the construction of Dhaka by-pass road project for
which they had proposed to set up a consortium of financiers.
</P>
<P>
The container terminal project at the Chittagong port, 224
kilometers southeast of here, with a proposed cost of 500 million
dollars, is another big project, he said.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations for the two power plants, and the western
region integrated power project for power generation and
distribution were at the advance stage. And these projects would
fetch about 2 billion dollars in the 1997-98 fiscal year, he
stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
