<HEADLINE> DPRK Official Calls for Dialogue with South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Monday called on
both sides of the Korean Peninsula to resume talks as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Kim Yong Sun, secretary of the Central Committee of the
Workers' Party, was speaking at a conference to commemorate the 10
guidelines of uniting the motherland initiated by the late Kim Il
Sung.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that to settle the dispute between the North and
the South and unite the nation through dialogue was a consistent
policy of the DPRK government.
</P>
<P>
He called on South Korea to "abandon its policies of conflict"
and work towards creating a favorable environment for dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Pyongyang proposed to Seoul through its Red
Cross society to resume government-level talks, and the south
formally accepted the offer on Monday. 
</P>
