<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand's Dilemma on Foreign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is a caricature published in a local newspaper Monday,
which reflects the sentiment of the Thai people.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Thai finance sector itself was in a love-hate
dilemma towards the entries of foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
The financial storm, which swept Thailand last July, has left
the country's banking sector shattered. The Thai government has to
clean up the messes with the help from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Under the IMF's prescription, Thailand began its big operation
on the ailing financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government led by Chuan Leekpai closed 56 of 58
suspended financial institutions and took over four banks which
were in poor condition soon after it took office last November.
</P>
<P>
The country's 15 commercial banks were required to greatly
increase their capitals, since the devaluation of the baht and
lands, which banks took as collaterals, have made their
non-performing loans soar.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, to promote Thai banks to the international standard
by the year 2000, the Bank of Thailand, the country's central
bank, is considering introducing tighter provisioning measures,
including changing the definition of non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed measures, the non-performing loans of Thai
banks will account for 40 percent of their total loans.
</P>
<P>
It is natural that local banks turned to their foreign
counterparts when seeking funds from domestic clients, who are
also cash-strapped, has been proved to be extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
A number of commercial banks announced their recapitalization
plans recently, which showed that many banks have been or will
inevitably be taken over by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The Development Bank of Singapore bought 50.27 percent of the
stake in Thai Danu Bank, while the ABN-Amro Bank of the
Netherlands followed suit by taking over 75 percent of the stake
of Bank of Asia.
</P>
<P>
ABN-Amro said it will buy all the stake of Bank of Asia by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Under its recapitalization plan, the Thai Farmers Bank, the
country's second largest, allowed a 49-percent foreign
shareholding instead of the previous 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the largest bank, Bangkok Bank, issued 400 million
new shares, mainly to foreign buyers, allowing the foreign
shareholding to increase from 25 percent to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts estimated that under the central bank's requirement of
capital increase, half of the local banks will see the majority of
their stake go into foreign hands.
</P>
<P>
Among the remaining 35 financial institutions, nine have been
taken over by foreigners, while the others were negotiating with
foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
It is widely acknowledged that foreign funds are indispensable
in reviving Thailand's financial sector and the economy as a
whole. That is why the government and Thai banks are making every
effort to lure more foreign banks and enterprises into the local
market.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, some Thai people fear that the country may be
degraded into an economic colony of western countries. That is a
dilemma for the Thai banks as well as for the country at present.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Meets French Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
said Monday that China would like to make concerted efforts with
France to further promote friendly and beneficial cooperation on
all aspects.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, Zhu said that
the relations between the two countries are developing fast along
the direction set by the Sino-Franco joint declaration. China and
France are carrying out positive cooperation in the political,
economic, scientific, cultural and military fields, he added.
</P>
<P>
More important, Zhu said, the joint declaration aiming to
establish a comprehensive partnership will escort the bilateral
relations into the next century.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that the Franco-Sino relations have entered its
best period. As a significant event in the bilateral relations,
Zhu's current two-day visit to France will help implement the
Franco-Sino joint declaration, he added
</P>
<P>
The joint declaration was signed by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and his French equivalent Jacques Chirac in Beijing last May.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier also expressed satisfaction that Jospin
continues the friendly policies toward China.
</P>
<P>
As a friend of China's, France is closely watching the
development in China, Jospin responded.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese economy is poised for a new take-off on the basis
of a broader opening to the world, and China is playing an
increasing role on the international stage," Jospin said. "These
will help realize a new balance in international relations."
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two premiers also agreed to strengthen
economic ties, particularly in the fields of energy and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
"French enterprises are very competitive and capable of
transferring advanced technologies through long-term and strategic
cooperation to China," the French premier noted as Zhu invited
French entrepreneurs to invest in China.
</P>
<P>
Both believed that trade between the two countries should reach
a higher level through common efforts.
</P>
<P>
Jospin gave a banquet after the meeting in honor of Zhu, who
will end his week-long trip to Britain and France and leave for
Beijing on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
