<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Schools Offer Installment of Fees for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 Training Courses
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- In view of the economic woe, many
educational institutions are offering learn-first-pay-later terms
to draw students to enroll in expensive courses, the Bangkok Post
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
People who enroll in training courses are now offered three-
or six-month installment terms.
</P>
<P>
According to Suphannee Somboontham, deputy director of
Chulalongkorn University's continuing education program, the terms
were being offered following the requests from many students and
applicants.
</P>
<P>
The move is proving a success in drawing a large number of
cash-strapped people, who want to improve their skills by taking
short-term courses, which are very expensive.
</P>
<P>
Suphannee said a 170-hour computer program development course
costs 54,000 baht (1,350 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
After the learn-first-pay-later method was introduced,
applications poured in as some 1,500 people applied for the 1,200
seats, she said.
</P>
<P>
Similar terms have been made available at assumption
university's education center. Last semester, 80 students paid by
monthly installment, and the director expects a sharp rise in next
semester.
</P>
<P>
Each student is charged 20,000-40,000 baht (500-1,000 dollars)
in tuition fees per semester in the assumption university.
</P>
<P>
Students said that the installment method enabled low-income
earners to improve their skills through expensive training
courses.
</P>
<P>
A widening of the payment system would put further education
within reach of more low-income people and others badly hit by the
economic slump, a student said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
