<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Phenomena Affects Myanmar's Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The EL Nino phenomena, which caused
widespread climatic variability in many places around the globe,
has only affected the climate of Myanmar partially, the country's
Meteorology and Hydrology Department said.
</P>
<P>
The strong EL Nino, which started in early 1997 and reached its
peak in early 1998, is weakening now, the New Light of Myanmar
newspaper Tuesday quoted the department as saying in its special
weather forecast for 1998.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that the maximum temperature in Myanmar's
divisions of Mandalay, Magway and Sagaing may reach 46 degree
centigrade in April and May, above the normal level in the months.
</P>
<P>
The onset of Monsoon rainfall, which usually comes between May
and October, will be late by two to three weeks, and slightly
below the normal level in the whole country, it said.
</P>
<P>
The number of storms and depressions in the Bay of Bengal and
Andaman Sea will also be less than the normal average, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
