<HEADLINE> WHO Sets Up Fund to Help Southeast Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization has
set up a special fund to help Southeast Asian nations tide over
the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Samlee Pliambangchang, a WHO official responsible for
Southeast Asian affairs, said the fund initially set 2 million
U.S. dollars for immediate assistance and technical support.
</P>
<P>
The WHO is to seek cooperation from donor agencies and other
international organizations in helping Southeast Asian countries,
particularly in obtaining basic necessities such as drugs and
medical devices, Tuesday's Bangkok Post quoted Dr. Samlee as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the WHO will give special attention to Indonesia which
is most affected by the crisis and is expected to face a shortage
of drugs.
</P>
<P>
The organization, he said, will ask India, a major Asian
producer of raw materials, to provide drugs on credit to
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
As for Thailand, Dr. Samlee said, technical assistance will be
provided in analyzing short and long-term measures required to
cope with health impacts due to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
WHO officials have said most of the health consequences
resulting from the economic crisis in Southeast Asia are not yet
manifested, therefore the organization should prepare itself to
respond to the health problems which have direct impact on the
public.
</P>
<P>
Thai Public Health Ministry recently set up a "health
intelligence unit" to cope with worsening health problems.
</P>
<P>
Pakdi Pothisiri, deputy permanent secretary for public health,
said the unit would coordinate with other state agencies,
including the National Economic and Social Development Board, the
Foreign Ministry and the Finance Ministry, in analyzing the
consequences of the economic crisis and propose measures to
relevant authorities accordingly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
