<HEADLINE> Philippines Sees Hike in Coconut Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Coconut Authority
(PCA) is targeting 3.5 million metric tons of coconut production,
in copra terms, by the year 2005, local television reports said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's coconut has improved and the prospects for an
increase in coconut farmers' income are bright with the help of
new technologies for coconut production and processing, PCA
administrator Virgilio David was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the PCA's plan, he coconut production is expected to
increase from 2.5 million metric tons to about 3 million metric
tons by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The PCA's coconut industry development plan is focused on
increasing farm production and productivity for the benefit of
millions of coconut farmers.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines remains the biggest supplier of coconut,
supplying about 60 percent of world-traded coconut products. About
80 percent of the country's coconut production goes to the
international market, while the remaining 20 percent is for
domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Statistics Office, coconut product
exports rose 2 percent to 173 million U.S. dollars in the first
two months of the year from the year-ago 169.8 million dollars.
Coconut exports include copra, coconut oil, desiccated coconut and
copra meal or cake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
