<HEADLINE> Economic Briefs From Latin-America (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Miguel Obando Bravo, cardinal of Managua, has
demanded the Nicaraguan government honestly administer the 1.8
million U.S. dollars that the international community has approved
for eliminating poverty in Nicaragua over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, a consultant group of the donating countries,
which met in Geneva, Switzerland, approved the package to boost
the economy.
</P>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA -- The Inter-American Development Bank has approved
a loan of 40 million U.S.dollars to improve the hospital network
in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be disbursed over the next four years and at
least six hospitals, which are among the most important in the
country, will be renovated and refurnished to improve services.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil, one of the world's largest wheat buyers,
imported five million tons of wheat at a cost of 813 million U.S.
dollars last year. About 77 percent of the imports, or 3.8 million
tons of wheat, came from Argentina.
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- The fishing industry along the Rio
Magdalena River in Colombia shrank by 27.3 percent from 1995
to 1997 due to water pollution, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
Fish output went down from 10,258 tons in 1995 to 7,449 tons in
1997. Pesticides, chemicals and hydrocarbons are among the main
pollutants in the river. 
</P>
</TEXT>
