<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't Allows Freezed Banks to Operate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
allow the seven Freezed banks to operate again after they have
repaid the Bank Indonesia (BI) liquidity funds, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
"The seven banks whose operation licenses have been revoked can
resume their activities if they can restore their own financial
viability and return the BI (central bank) liquidity funds they
have used," Chairman of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency
(IBRA)Iwan Prawiranate said here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the government announced the suspension of seven
private commercial banks and placing of another seven banks under
the management of IBRA, saying the move is part of the ongoing
banking reforms to restore its reputation and regain the
confidence of people at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Iwan said the operations of the seven banks were frozen because
they had been using liquidity funds of BI in excess of 500 percent
of their paid-up capital and equal to or in excess of 75 percent
of their total assets.
</P>
<P>
The other seven banks placed under IBRA control had been using
BI liquidity funds totaling more than 2 trillion rupiah (about 240
million U.S. dollars) and also in excess of 500 percent of their
total equity.
</P>
<P>
IBRA deputy chairperson Rind Suwandi also said the IBRA hoped
the government to take over the equity of the seven banks now
under the agency's management so that they can become healthy
again.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, BI Governor Syahril Sabirin said that no deadline
had been given to the troubled banks now under supervision of
IBRA.
</P>
<P>
"Let us just wait and see their development. Hopefully they can
be healthy and sound soon," Antara quoted the governor as saying.
</P>
<P>
As many as 54 troubled banks now are under the supervision of
IBRA, said the governor.
</P>
<P>
According to a monetary reform agreement signed last year
between the Indonesian government and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF), the Indonesian government had closed down 16 private
banks at the end of October last year in a bid to restore the
healthy operation of the financial system and improve the
efficiency of the country's banking industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Landscape Paintings to Be Exhibited in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-six Russian landscape
paintings of Isaak Levitan and his contemporaries will be
exhibited in the China National Art Gallery April 10-28, according
to an official from China's Ministry of Culture.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference for the exhibition Monday, Xi Jingzhi,
professor of the Central Academy of Fine Arts, said that in the
second half of the 19th century the Russian landscape school had
reached its peak.
</P>
<P>
Levitan, who died at 39, was representatives of landscape
painters in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech, Russian ambassador to China Igor
A. Rogachev said Levitan's landscape paintings compare favorably
with the poetry of Alexander Pushkin and Mikhail Lermontov, with
prose of Nikolay Turgenev and Leo Tolstoy, with music of Peter
Tchaikovsky and Sergey Rakhmaninov.
</P>
<P>
The total 86 works, which come from four local museums in
Russia, includes the masterpieces of Levitan and other masters
such as "Lake" and "The Coming Back of Rooks," according to the
Ministry of Culture, which is the major sponsor of the
exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Says Indonesia to Implement Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank envoy said that
Indonesia will implement the economic reforms agreed with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), as it is important to gain
international and domestic market confidence.
</P>
<P>
"I have a great confidence. The government is negotiating the
program, and it is reflecting seriousness in implementing it,"
World Bank Vice President for Asia Pacific Region, Jean-Michel
Severino said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Severino made his response to international community doubt on
the country's willingness in implementing the reform program
negotiated with the IMF, Antara News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Negotiation between the Indonesian government and the IMF that
will be over in the next few days is expected to result in a
strong and credible package, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have been negotiating here since March 18 to
review Indonesia's economic reform program tied to the IMF's 43
billion U.S. dollar aid to the country.
</P>
<P>
The IMF gave the first 3-billion-dollar tranche to Indonesia in
December last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the second 3-billion-dollar tranche was delayed
pending a review of the progress made by the Indonesian government
in implementing the IMF-prescribed economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank's country director for Indonesia,
Dennis de Tray said the government should also recognize that
there is no magic medicine to go through the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank plans to disburse 4.5 billion dollars of fund
over the next three years to support Indonesia's economic recovery
and help it return to growth and development.
</P>
<P>
The fund will emphasize a framework for macroeconomic
stability, financial reform, competition policy and regulatory
reform, sustained economic growth and the setting of social safety
nets for the poor and other vulnerable groups.
</P>
<P>
Of the total pledge, the World Bank will contribute 2 billion
dollars to support a financial sector restructuring program this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
