<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Province Bans Traditional Burials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- In a move to save its farmland by
changing some traditional funeral practices, south China's
Guangdong Province has decided to halt the practice of burying the
dead.
</P>
<P>
From this year, the province will no longer give permission for
most burials and will encourage cremation of the dead, according
to Saturday's Yangtze Evening News, and will no longer give
permission for new cemeteries, which have become a fairly
lucrative business in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is known for its sticking to the old practice of
burying people and for its funeral rituals. The cremation rate in
the province is estimated at 23.5 percent, or 10 percentage points
lower than the nation's average.
</P>
<P>
In several cities, the rate has remained below 5 percent, while
in Shenzhen, the prosperous special economic zone, the rate
climbed to 97.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial civil affairs department, about
270,000 people have been buried each year in recent years,
resulting in an annual loss of at least 266 hectares of land. And
in some places, people have destroyed forests to make room for the
dead, in some cases building elaborate cemetaries for their own or
for family members' use in future.
</P>
<P>
Although the provincial government is determined to halt this
practice, one official says that the road to reform is going to be
a bumpy one.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
