<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Aids Farmers, But Still Drought Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The drought that has plagued north
China's farms for months and threatened major winter wheat growing
areas has eased, according to an official from the State
Drought-Prevention Office (SDPO).
</P>
<P>
Rain this month and last has brought an average of 20 to 30
millimeters of precipitation to most of north China's winter wheat
producers between the Yellow and the Huaihe rivers, with some
areas receiving an average of 40-60 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the growth of winter wheat in China's major
producing areas is as good as that of the same period in 1997 when
there was a bumper summer harvest, said the SDPO official.
</P>
<P>
"Rainfall has essentially eased the drought threatening the
growth of winter wheat in northern parts of Jiangsu and Anhui
provinces and most parts of Henan, Shandong, Shanxi and Shaanxi."
</P>
<P>
The official said the rains have not only been beneficial to
winter wheat and other transplanted seeds but that the moister soil
has made spring sowing much easier.
</P>
<P>
While optimistic about the soil moisture brought by the recent
rainfalls, one in mid-March, the other between the end of March
and April 2, the SDPO official cautioned farmers not to ignore the
possibility of worse drought to come, perhaps in May.
</P>
<P>
At present, 11 million hectares of farmland to be used for
crops sown in spring and reaped in autumn are suffering from poor
soil moisture because of severe drought in previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three weeks, eastern parts of northeast China,
the country's largest autumn harvest area and most important
commodity grain producer, received only 10-20 millimeters of
rainfall. Although enough to improve soil moisture, it was not
enough to alleviate the drought there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
