<HEADLINE> Inflation Rate Dips in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' inflation rate, as
measured by the consumer index, declined a bit in March to 7.3
percent from an 18-month high of 7.4 percent in February this
year, according to the latest report from the National Statistics
Office.
</P>
<P>
In the report published Tuesday, Socio-economic Planning
Secretary Cielito Habito said the slowdown was a result of the
government's efforts in addressing the price situation.
</P>
<P>
But the latest inflation figure was higher than an earlier
projected target of less than 7 percent by the government for
March.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Fenix, president of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce
and Industry, attributed the slight decline in inflation level to
the oil price rollback ordered by the Energy Regulatory Board.
</P>
<P>
Fenix also cited the lower campaign spending as another
contributory factor to the lower inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
But many economists were still sticking to their double-digit
inflation projection in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso has fallen more than 30 percent since its
effective devaluation in July last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
