<HEADLINE> Myanmar Steps Up Crackdown on Prostitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities will crack
down practice of prostitution by amending the related existing law
and meting out deterrent punishment to offenders.
</P>
<P>
According to the Law Amending the Suppression of Prostitution
Act (1949) enacted on Monday, those who break the law will be
punished with a prison term of up to five years and fine.
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar Tuesday said
the law was amended in order to protect young women against being
degenerated and prevent the spread of HIV virus and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Some persons are running the prostitution business in the guise
of opening massage parlors or beauty parlors in some cities of the
country including Yangon, the report added. 
</P>
