<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pak-Canada Relations to Grow Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Canada will further
enhance their existing friendly and cooperative relations in
various fields, particularly in trade and economic areas.
</P>
<P>
This was emphasized by both the countries during a four-day
state visit to Pakistan by Canadian Governor General Romero
Leblanc, which concluded on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Leblanc was the first head of state from Canada to have visited
this South Asian nation during the last half a century, although
Canada established formal diplomatic relations with Pakistan
within two weeks of the inception of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Among the entourage of the Canadian Governor General were many
business men. This indicated Canada's great interest in developing
trade and economic relations with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
At a business luncheon held in honor of Leblanc, Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said that his country attached great
importance to "translating deep friendship with Canada into a
mutually beneficial and vibrant economic cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Sharif made special reference to the government's newly
announced investment policy, saying "all sectors of the economy,
including agriculture, service industry, infrastructure and social
sector are open for investment on repatriable basis."
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has taken attractive investment
incentives, and foreign investment enjoy complete protection under
laws in the country, Sharif added.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was confident that with continued efforts by both the
governments and business people, the current two-way trade and the
level of Canadian investment in Pakistan will be increased
manifold.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Pakistan, Leblanc and his party held
wide-ranging talks with the Pakistani leaders and business men.
The two countries expressed their strong desire to further the
mutual beneficial economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and Canada are now working together on environmental
protection, regulation of energy, financial credit systems, health
care and education. "Through all our cooperation, our two
countries have built a strong foundation for growth in trade and
in mutual prosperity," Leblanc said.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with the Governor General, President Tariq
Tarar said that the visit would strengthen the bilateral relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Leblanc said the two countries have an actively-evolving
relations in the field of trade and investment, and share common
views on many issues of international importance. The governor
General also stressed the need for cultural exchange which, he
termed as "an investment" for the future.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the capital city of Islamabad, the visit also took
Leblanc to Pakistan's second largest city of Lahore, where he also
had meetings with the business sector.
</P>
<P>
Leblanc held that prospects of increasing economic cooperation
between the two countries are very bright.
</P>
<P>
Canada wants to help Pakistan bring development and prosperity
for its people. And for this purpose, investment can play a key
role, he said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Canada and Pakistan are close partners in the
field of trade and economic affairs and "in this area our
cooperation has been very positive and successful."
</P>
<P>
Besides, their bilateral talks also covered regional and
international issues of mutual interests, peace and stability in
South Asia and the Pak-Indian relationship in particular.
</P>
<P>
Leblanc expressed the hope Pakistan and India, the two South
Asian nations, with which Canada enjoys cordial relations, will
resolve their outstanding issues in a spirit of accommodation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
