<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers are as follows:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- French President Jacques Chirac met visiting Chinese Premier
Zhu Rongji Monday at the Elysee Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said he was pleased that Premier Zhu visited France soon
after he took office, and he was glad to receive him.
</P>
<P>
-- To ensure a good summer grain harvest, central China's Henan
Province has sent more than 10,000 government officials and
agriculture experts to villages across the province. The experts
will provide technology help for local farmers.
</P>
<P>
-- China is to invest 135 million yuan (16.2 million US
dollars) to set up a major crustal movement monitoring network,
which will provide valuable statistics and scientific information
for earthquake research and prediction.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- On his first tour to France as premier of China, Zhu Rongji
has been cordially received by his hosts since his arrival on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
To honor the Chinese leader, French President Jacques Chirac
hosted a luncheon at the Elysee Presidential Palace on Monday.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji Monday called on French
enterprises to be more engaged in China, as the country is the
best for investment in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"I think China is the best place for investment in Asia. But
it is up to you to decide. Don't lose this opportunity," said
Zhu when addressing more than 200 heads of French enterprises
at a breakfast organized by France's national employers'
association CNPF.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Students taking the national college entrance examinations
will have to get used to a new system from next year.
</P>
<P>
The new "3+X" method means that students will have examinations
in three subjects -- Chinese, mathematics and English -- plus X
(at least one other) subjects designated by colleges.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Defence Minister Chi Haotian talked with Ukrainian
counterpart Alexander Kuzmuk in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission and
a State councillor, said Kuzmuk's visit will inject new impetus
into the growth of friendly relations between the countries --
oriented towards the 21st century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
