<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina, Italy Sign Cooperation Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem and Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi signed a cooperation
treaty Monday, aimed at helping promote trade relations between the
countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Argentine Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella and
Italian Deputy Foreign Minister Patrizia Toia signed an accord on
cultural and education cooperation.
</P>
<P>
After the signature, Prodi made a speech at a stock exchange in
Buenos Aires, emphasizing the importance of strengthening ties
between the European Union and Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Prime Minister arrived here Sunday for a two-day
visit in accordance with the Joint Declaration signed in Bologna
on December 3 last year when Menem visited Italy.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the trade volume between the two nations totalled
about 3.87 billion U.S. dollars, while the Italian investments in
Argentina amounted to four billion dollars, the sixth biggest
investor to Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
