<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said here Monday
that the relations between France and China have entered the best
period in history.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with visiting Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, Jospin said
Zhu's visit, as an important event in the bilateral relations,
will further promote the implementation of the joint declaration
signed last May by Chinese President Jiang Zemin and French
President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who is here for a two-day official visit, said that the
elan of development of the bilateral ties has been very strong
over the past few years. (France-China-Premier)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan, as a sovereign state, has the right to
develop missiles which is of fundamental relevance to its national
security, a foreign office spokesman said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a crowded news conference, the spokesman confirmed
that Pakistan successfully carried out a test Monday on the
surface-to-surface Hatf-V (Ghauri) missile, which has a range of
1,500 kilometers and can carry a payload of 700 kilograms
"overland."
</P>
<P>
He said the test, using a missile developed with Pakistan's own
materials and technology, represented "a landmark" in the
country's missile and satellite launching
program. (Pakistan-Missile-Development)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia Monday sharply denounced a blast near the
Russian Embassy in Riga, Latvia's capital, describing the incident
as "outrageous."
</P>
<P>
The bomb went off 35 meters from the Russian Embassy at 2300
GMT Sunday. Four cars were damaged, but there were no casualties,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The blast provided new grounds for even greater concern over
anti-Russian terrorist activities and rising nationalism and
extremism in the Baltic nation, said the Russian Foreign
Ministry. (Russia-Latvia-Blast) 
</P>
</TEXT>
