<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Worries about Japanese Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Trade Development
Board (TRADENZ) has expressed concern over the Japanese economy
being hit by the falling yen and sharemarket.
</P>
<P>
TRADENZ regional manager Eugene Bowen said New Zealand's
exports to Japan are expected to fall this year, the Wellington
newspaper "The Dominion" reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is agreed it is going to be a bad year for Japan," he
noted. But he expected New Zealand trade with Japan will drop less
than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, out trade will go down in calendar 1998 in a single-
digit margin, mostly driven by wood products," Bowen stated.
</P>
<P>
Japan is New Zealand's largest forestry products export market,
taking about a third of overseas sales.
</P>
<P>
It is also New Zealand's second-largest export market after
Australia. The two-way trade stood at 6 billion N.Z. dollars
(about 4 billion U.S. dollars) last year, in which New Zealand
exports amounted to 3.2 billion NZ dollars (About 2.13 billion
U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
