<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Buy British Submarines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Defense Minister Art
Eggleton said Monday that Canada will buy four British submarines.
</P>
<P>
The minister confirmed recent reports that the cabinet has
decided on the four used diesel subs in order to replace Canada's
three aging Oberon-class ones.
</P>
<P>
The British Upholder-class subs were built in the early 1990s
and mothballed soon after their delivery after the British navy
decided on nuclear-powered ships.
</P>
<P>
The four Upholders cost Britain a total of 2.28 billion dollars
(1.6 billion USD) to build.
</P>
<P>
Canada is expected to pay 610 million dollars for the four
subs, along with 140 million dollars that will be spent on
training and spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The submarines are to be delivered to Canada starting from
2000, according to reports here.
</P>
<P>
Canada's current subs were built by the British in the 1960s.
For years, Canada's navy has been arguing for new subs as
replacements of the old.
</P>
<P>
With the purchase, Canada's navy will have subs that are
quieter, faster, deeper-diving and have smaller crews than the old
ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
