<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Procedure Fails Improving Ties with Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- In contrast to warm welcome
American wrestlers had received in Iran, Iranian wrestlers have
suffered strict examinations when they arrived in Chicago last
week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department said on Monday offered no apology to
Iran for the treatment, saying federal law requires such
procedures for unofficial, nonimmigrant visitors from four
countries -- Iran, Iraq, Libya and Sudan -- that are on unfriendly
terms with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody has made a mistake here by implementing the existing
regulations," spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington may alter the practice in the future if
relations with Tehran continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
"We will be discussing it at the State Department to make sure
the procedures are appropriate in these tapes of visits," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian wrestling team was detained for two hours in
Chicago last week when they flew in the United States. They were
photographed and fingerprinted. The episode left the Iranian
government convinced there was no shift at all in Washington's
policy toward Tehran.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said the State Department was not aware that
any such procedure would be applied against the Iranians, given
the adminsitrattion's eagerness for an incident-free visit.
</P>
<P>
Foley hoped the bad feelings over the treatment accorded to
the Iranian wrestlers would pass quickly.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to stress, first and foremost, the fact that
the Iranian wrestlers are, indeed, welcome visitors in the
United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And so in spite of what may have happened at their arrival
in Chicago, this should not in any way be interpreted as a
lessening of our commitment to facilitating these exchanges and
this dialogue at that sort of level," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
