<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Urged to Ratify Nuclear Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Administration is
urging the U.S. Senate to ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT), U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations William Richardson
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement at the U.N. Headquarters, Richardson said
the United States applauses the efforts of Britain and France to
ratify the CTBT today.
</P>
<P>
"This is a milestone in the global efforts to reduce the
nuclear threat," he said adding that the the U.S. (Administration)
has asked the U.S. Senate to give its advice and consent to the
CTBT this year."
</P>
<P>
"We urge the Senate to approve it soon," he continued.
</P>
<P>
"This CTBT will significantly further our nuclear
non-proliferation and arms control objectives and strengthen
international security," Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
Britain and France announced here this morning their
ratification of CTBT, following the other 11 countries to ratify
the treaty signed by 149 countries since it was opened for
signature on September 24, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 11 countries are Austria, Czech Republic, Fiji, Japan,
Micronesia, Mongolia, Peru, Qatar, Slovakia, Turkmenistan, and
Uzbekistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
