<HEADLINE> Dow Vaults over 9,000 Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 6 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks closed above
9,000 points for the first time, vaulting into record territory
Monday on news of a major financial services merger.
</P>
<P>
At the sound of closing bell, the Dow Jones industrial average
stopped at 9,033.23, up 49.82 over the previous session. The
barometer of blue-chip stocks hit 9,000 for the first time early
Friday, only to close nearly 17 points short.
</P>
<P>
At one point early today, the Dow surged up more than 111
points to 9,094.76.
</P>
<P>
The record closing came little more than five months after the
Dow Jones industrial average tumbled below 7,000.
</P>
<P>
The New York Stock Exchange also set a record today.
</P>
<P>
The buying spree followed the announcement that Citicorp and
Travelers Group are merging in a record 70-billion-U.S. dollar
deal. The pact unites the nation's second-biggest bank and a
leading provider of financial services ranging from trading stocks
to insurance.
</P>
<P>
The news made Travelers Group the most-traded stock on the New
York Stock Exchange, and drove up the values of bank and financial
services stocks at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Both Travelers and Citicorp rose by big margins. Citicorp
gained a hefty 37 to more than 180 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Despite the rise in the Dow, declining issues outnumbered
advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where
volume came to 603 million shares, below Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
The S&AMP;P 500 list was down 1.31 at 1,121.39. The NYSE composite
index was up 0.09 at 583.17 -- surpassing the record hit on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index was down 26.23 at
1,889.17 and the American Stock Exchange composite index was down
4.41 at 742.78.  
</P>
</TEXT>
