<HEADLINE> U.S. Plans New $20 Note Design </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The design for the Series 1996
20 U.S. dollar note, the first redesigned U.S. currency note will
be unveiled next month by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Rubin and Chairman Greenspan will unveil the new bill
on May 20, at the Bureau of Engraving and Printing, Washington,
according to an announcement from the Treasury Department here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new 20 dollar note will enter circulation in the fall of
1998. It is commonly used in daily commerce and is the bill most
often dispensed by Automated Teller Machines (ATMs). The 20 dollar
note is the third in the U.S. currency series to include new and
modified security features to deter counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
The Series 1996 100 dollar was issued in March 1996 and the
redesigned 50 dollar note in October last year.
</P>
<P>
Like the new 50 dollar note, the redesigned 20 note will
include a large dark numeral on a light background on the back of
the note that will make it easier for people with low vision to
identify the note. 
</P>
</TEXT>
