<HEADLINE> Egypt: Peace Revivable If Israel Reconsiders Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said on Monday that it is still possible to pull the Mideast peace
process out of its current impasse if Israel reconsiders its
stance toward a comprehensive Arab-Israeli peace.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that Egypt is holding intensive
consultations with the United States, European Union, Arabs,
Palestinians and Israelis on ways of rescuing the stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on his recent contacts with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, Moussa said that Netanyahu affirmed his
determination to continue the peace process and his hope to reach
a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt considers these statements as a good sign, but they need
a positive action to be realized," he said, urging the Israeli
leader to drop his hardline policies on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks came to a standstill in
March last year when Israel broke ground for the construction of a
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as
the capital of their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
Cairo's contacts with Arab countries are designed to make a
complete evaluation of the current state of the peace process and
crystalize a sound Arab stance, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are also underway to persuade the U.S. to make public
its peace initiative to pressure Israel into softening its
hardline position, he said.
</P>
<P>
Washington has reportedly outlined a plan calling on Israel to
withdraw troops from 13.1 percent of the West Bank over 12 weeks,
accompanied by security cooperation with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross failed to win the acceptance
of the plan from Israel and the Palestinians during his recent
shuttle between the leaders of the two sides. The U.S. has yet
to make public the plan for fear of putting pressure on Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
