<HEADLINE> Ross: Israel, Palestinians Want Peace Process to Go on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis
Ross said on Monday that both the Israelis and Palestinians
intended to find a way to break the year-long deadlock on the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an annual meeting of the Anti-Defamation League,
an American Jewish organization, Ross said the U.S.-guided
process was resilient.
</P>
<P>
But he neither gave any details of his four-day futile
diplomacy in the region last week, nor shed any light on what
the Clinton administration might do next.
</P>
<P>
The White House said earlier that Ross and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright would brief President Bill Clinton on the
difficult situation for reviving the deadlocked peace process in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"Ross will review where we are in the peace process," a White
House spokeswoman said. She did not make any elaboration on the
evening briefing.
</P>
<P>
Albright said in Port-of Spain, Trinidad, she would go to the
White House after a Caribbean foreign ministers meeting and give
President Clinton a report on Ross' trip.
</P>
<P>
"It will be during that meeting that we will consider what our
next steps will be," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright also said in a letter to Democratic Senator Carl
Levin that the Clinton administration would remain determined to
work privately and "without public disclosure" of the proposals
Ross had offered to both the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has disclosed and rejected the U.S. proposals
which requires Israel to further cede 13.1 percent of the West
Bank to the Palestinians who in return would take steps to meet
Israel's request for security.
</P>
<P>
At the annual meeting of the Anti-Defamation League, Israeli
Ambassador Eliahu Ben-Elissar said both Israel and the
Palestinians would have to make compromises to get talks between
the two sides resumed.
</P>
<P>
"Peace means compromise, peace means concession, and we are
ready," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Ambassador Ahmed Maher Al Sayed, for his part,
criticized Israel's stance toward the Palestinians.  
</P>
