<HEADLINE> Greek Consumers Boycott Farm Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Greek consumers Monday began to
boycott meat and farm products in protest against the recent price
hikes stemming from the drachma's 14-percent devaluation and
rainstorms that swept the country.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Consumers' Institute (INKA) hoped that the five-day
boycott would force the national producers and merchants to reduce
prices.
</P>
<P>
The most expensive markets in Greece were reported to be in the
islands of Rhodes, Corfu and Crete.
</P>
<P>
Wishing to join the European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU)
in 2001, Greece recently speeded up its economic reform pace by
allowing its national currency to join the European exchange rate
mechanism (ERM) as of March 14.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government has decided to intensify money market
checks to prevent profiteering while calling on the Greek business
world and traders not to pass on the consequences of the
devaluation to prices by exercising self restraint. 
</P>
