<DOCNO> XIE19980407.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Chip to Cut PC Prices Deeply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Semiconductor
Corp. said today that a new chip could drive personal computer
prices to less than 400 U.S. dollars by next year, likely to spur
a new price cutting wave.
</P>
<P>
The company is developing a chip that combines a
micro-processor with circuitry of more than a dozen additional
chips needed to make a PC, which is regarded as being able to
substantially reduce manufacturing costs, the Wall Street Journal
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We've got top-brand customers working with us on this," Brian
Halla, National's chairman and chief executive officer, was quoted
as saying. The company did not reveal the potential customers yet.
</P>
<P>
The paper said it won't be easy to have an impact. Intel
supplies close to 90 percent of the microprocessors used in PCs
and has ample resources to counter most of its rivals' development
plans.
</P>
<P>
The company also said that used in a conventional portable
computer, the PC-on-a-chip could enable a machine to last for nine
hours on battery power, or long enough for a trans-Pacific flight,
Halla said.
</P>
<P>
Many of today's chips have circuits that are about 0.35 microns
wide, or one-300th the width of a human hair. That is enough to
put about seven million transistors on a chip. National and other
companies are moving to 0.25-micron chips this year, enough for
roughly 30 million to 50 million transistors. By the end of next
year, the company expects to hit dimensions of 0.18 microns,
allowing for as many as 100 million transistors, more than enough
to handle most functions of a computer on one piece of silicon.
</P>
<P>
National Semiconductor Corp last year bought Cyrix Corp., a
microprocessor maker whose integrated Media GX chip helped Compaq
computer Corp. stimulated the sub-1,000 U.S. dollar PC market in
January 1997.
</P>
<P>
One chain of retail stores in the U.S. already is selling a
Cyrix-based machine for 499 U.S. dollars, without a monitor. By
comparison, the least-expensive machines based on Intel chips run
for about 800 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts question the company's capability of keeping up
the running speed of PC while integrate more components. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
